Iz analizy vy≈°e vidƒõli jesmo, ≈æe dobra simetrija med≈æu latiniceju i kiriliceju trƒõbovala by byti: ili 3:3, ƒçto znaƒçi "imati latiniƒçne analogy" za: —ô/—ö, —ô—ò/—ö—ò, –ª—ò/–Ω—ò. abo 1:1 (lj-—ô, nj-—ö). Imenno zato najprosty variant by byl koristati samo ligatury —ô/—ö v kirilici: izguba etimologiƒçnoj informacije byla by ravna med≈æu alfabetami; pytanje najvy≈°e fonetiƒçno razumlivogo izgovora slova nikogdy ne mo≈æe byti polno adresovano bez pogledanja na etimologiƒçny zapis slova; vizualno, zapis –∑–Ω–∞—ö–µ i –ø–∏—Ç–∞—ö–µ ne zlo by koreloval s –∑–Ω–∞–Ω—å–µ üá∑üá∫, –ø–∏—Ç–∞–Ω–Ω—è üá∫üá¶, –ø–∏—Ç–∞–Ω–µ üáßüá¨. Trƒõba tako≈æe pripomnƒõti ƒçitateljam nemo≈ænost polnogo programatiƒçnogo rƒõ≈°enja problema s —ô/–ª—ò i —ö/–Ω—ò, ktoro ranƒõje proponovalo se kako alternativa vsakoj reformƒõ jezyka. Na ≈æalost, ne vsaky raz mo≈æno izjaviti s 100% uvƒõrjenostju ƒçto znaƒçi nƒõkaka rƒõƒç ‚Äì sut homonimy v med≈æuslovjanskom leksikonu, i v takoj situaciji, jedino algoritmy s umƒõtnoju inteligencijeju (AI) budut smogti toƒçno skazati ƒçto to jest, napr: usiljam kako v ja usiljam (glagol s tvrdym L) abo hvala usiƒ∫jam (imennik s mekkym L). Jaroslav Sergƒõjev

Prvo, ƒçitatelj mo≈æe je≈°ƒçe proƒçitati tutoj dokument, kde obgovarjali se mnoge ine propozicije i pytanja okolo poslƒõdic raznyh reform: Med≈æuslovjansko Vƒõƒçe (22.06.2024) Dalje, trƒõbujemo obgovoriti s pomoƒçnikami razvoja med≈æuslovjanskogo jezyka argumenty i kontrargumenty vsakoj propozicije v komentarah ni≈æe . I, v koncu, Med≈æuslovjanska Jezyƒçna Komisija glasuje za jedin iz variantov.

Interslavic is a constructed auxiliary language designed to be mutually intelligible for speakers of various Slavic languages. It draws from a common base of Slavic vocabulary and grammar. Example Med≈æuslovjansky jest jezyk razumlivy priblizno vsim slovjansko-jezyƒçnym ljudam bez uƒçenja. –ú–µ–¥–∂—É—Å–ª–æ–≤—ò–∞–Ω—Å–∫—ã —ò–µ—Å—Ç —ò–µ–∑—ã–∫ —Ä–∞–∑—É–º–ª–∏–≤—ã –ø—Ä–∏–±–ª–∏–∑–Ω–æ –≤—Å–∏–º —Å–ª–æ–≤—ò–∞–Ω—Å–∫–æ-—ò–µ–∑—ã—á–Ω—ã–º —ô—É–¥–∞–º –±–µ–∑ —É—á–µ–Ω—ò–∞.

Being an auxiliary language means that Interslavic does not intend to replace any living Slavic languages or serve as a language for high literature ‚Äî we already have vibrant, living languages for those purposes. Instead, its goal is to aid in communication between people from different linguistic backgrounds.

If you're already familiar with a Slavic language: Skim through Interslavic Grammar and observe any Interslavic text for guidance, for instance, The Little Prince. Refer to Interslavic Dictionary for translating words and understanding their declensions. Begin composing sentences using the dictionary. Don't be afraid ‚Äì most Slavic languages have similar enough grammar and vocabulary. Expect several months of dedicated learning and practice to become proficient in writing and speaking Interslavic. If you don't know a Slavic language: Review the Slovianto tutorial for an introductory language overview. Join the Interslavic community on Discord and Facebook for the latest advice on approaches that suit your needs.
documents.s: How to learn and use Interslavic?

documents.t: Interslavic has two levels of proficiency: standard and advanced. For Slavic native speakers, learning the standard level of Interslavic should not take a long time ‚Äì many people reported their learning experience as non-intensive, usually pursued during their free time, and it took them: 2-3 weeks of study to write confidently; 1.5-3 months to engage in basic conversations; 8-10 months to speak confidently on a wide range of topics. However, the required time is individual and may vary significantly from person to person. If you do not speak Slavic languages, it will take considerably longer to learn Interslavic.
documents.s: How long does it take to learn Interslavic?

documents.t: No. A true statement: many Slavs can understand Interslavic well enough without any prior study if they have a strong command of their native Slavic language, focus, and a desire to understand.
documents.s: Is it true that all Slavs can understand Interslavic?

documents.t: Rather not. Learning Interslavic improves your comprehension of other Slavic languages, but it is not a shortcut - to get a good grasp of any particular language, you'll have to learn it specifically.
documents.s: If I learn Interslavic, will I understand other Slavic languages?

documents.t: It varies from person to person. Many Interslavic speakers have reported being able to understand speakers of other Slavic languages, but they also noted that their comprehension abilities differ depending on the specific language.
documents.s: If I speak my native Slavic language to an Interslavic speaker, will they understand me?

documents.t: The goal of Interslavic is to be immediately accessible and understandable without prior learning. Words like "kalendar" or "kompjuter" are known to all Slavs; therefore, such words get included in the Interslavic lexicon.
documents.s: Why does Interslavic include non-Slavic words, such as "kalendar"?

documents.t: The Interslavic Latin alphabet has only four letters with diacritics: ƒå tÕ° É, ≈†  Ç, ≈Ω  í, ƒö j…õ. However, some people use additional diacritics and letters to memorize Slavic etymology, so occasionally, you might encounter weird words like ƒáuƒëi, otƒóc, d»Ø≈æƒè, grƒô≈∫, b≈≥de, hl√•d, —Å—´–≥–ª”ë—Å—ä–∫, —Ç—£—Ö, –≥—´–±–æ—≠, –ø–æ–∫–∞–∑—É—•—Ç. While etymological scripts may help improve pronunciation in advanced stages, they often degrade written text comprehension and are considered non-standard. Therefore, if you are just starting to learn Interslavic, it is recommended to stick to the standard Latin or Cyrillic alphabet and focus on mastering the basics. Tip If you approach Interslavic as a platform for studying other Slavic languages, rather than a standalone language, it might be beneficial to enable the etymological script in the Interslavic Dictionary from the day one, so you don't have to relearn the words later.
documents.s: What are those weird diacritics and letters some people use in Interslavic?

documents.t: There are several solutions for this: Pick one of our keyboard layouts for your operating system. If you cannot find or install a custom keyboard: standard Interslavic can be written on a Czech keyboard, simplified Interslavic (without ƒö/–Ñ and Y/–´) ‚Äì also on a Croatian, Serbian or Slovenian keyboard. If you find all this too complicated, you may substitute problematic letters with letters available on your keyboard, too: Poles can write CZ instead of ƒå, SZ instead of ≈†, ≈ª instead of ≈Ω, etc. East Slavs and Bulgarians can write –ô or –Ü instead of J, –õ–¨ instead of –â, –ù–¨ instead of –ä, etc. For details, see representation of problematic characters and remember that such variants might worsen intelligibility. For ad-hoc use, you can always use the transliterator or the extended transliterator (for standard and etymological orthography, respectively) to get the desired result.
documents.s: How can I write Interslavic on my own keyboard?

documents.t: Yes, there is a prototype of an automatic translator for Interslavic available. It is functional but still requires further development and improvement by programmers.
documents.s: Is there an automatic translator for Interslavic?

documents.t: No, there is no Duolingo course available right now.
documents.s: Is there a Duolingo course for Interslavic?

documents.t: Interslavic is an evolving project, and it is possible that you may not be able to find a specific word in the dictionary. In that case: look for synonyms first; search using Ma≈°ina bot on the Discord server or Telegram Messenger; ask Interslavic speakers on the Discord server to help you.
documents.s: Help! I can't find a word!

documents.t: Yes, there is various content available in Interslavic: Movies (YouTube playlist) Songs (YouTube playlist) In the Resources section, you can find more Interslavic books, short stories, audiobooks, poems, and songs.
documents.s: Are there any movies, music, or books in Interslavic?

documents.t: Interslavic language content is a valuable resource for both learners and native speakers of Slavic languages interested in understanding it without prior study. Based on the comments we get, the majority of viewers of Interslavic content belong to the latter group.
documents.s: Who needs content in Interslavic: movies, music, texts?

documents.t: Vojtƒõch Merunka and Jan van Steenbergen, principal authors of the modern Interslavic, have noted that while English is a global language, it can be challenging for Slavic speakers due to its unique orthography, mixed vocabulary, irregular grammar, and peculiar phonetics. Interslavic aims to facilitate communication within the Slavic community, preserving cultural nuances that might be lost when using a non-Slavic language. See more comparisons between Interslavic and other languages here.
documents.s: Why do we need Interslavic if there is English everywhere?

documents.t: Unfortunately, without prior learning, no single natural Slavic language can serve as a mutually intelligible means of communication for all Slavic speakers.
documents.s: Can't we just choose a natural Slavic language to serve as the Interslavic language?

documents.t: No, Interslavic is a non-political linguistic project. Its objective is to foster communication in tourism, culture, and business.
documents.s: Does Interslavic aim to unite the countries into a single Slavic state?

documents.t: Interslavic is not a form of Pan-Slavism and does not endorse any political stance. It is a purely linguistic project.
documents.s: What political stance does Interslavic support? Is it a form of Pan-Slavism?

documents.t: Interslavic is a natural and very broadly understandable language for Slavs. It is entirely based on forms common to the Slavic languages, and when no common forms exist, on majority solutions. It has grammatical gender, six cases plus an optional vocative, verbal aspect and full conjugation ‚Äì things that virtually every Slav is familiar with. In addition, it also contains some material that is absent in most Slavic languages, but knowledge of which can be of great help in understanding the languages that use it. Compared to the natural Slavic languages, this grammar model is still fairly simple and regular. Exceptions are rare and most irregularity is eliminated with means provided by the Slavic languages themselves, without introducing any artificiality. This grammar model is primarily intended for communication between Slavs of different nationalities, but can of course also be used by non-Slavs who want to be able to communicate on a more serious level. It is suitable for contacts and publications, but also as a means to gain insight into the nature of Slavic.

Adjectives match with the noun they modify in gender, case and number. Declension is always regular. However, three things are to be remembered: Adjectives are heavily affected by the o/e and y/i rules, which means that a distinction is made between hard stems and soft stems: if the stem ends in ≈°, ≈æ, ƒç or j, then every -o- becomes -e- and every -y- becomes -i-. Just like in the case of nouns, the accusative of has the same form as the genitive when the corresponding noun is masculine and animate, both singular and plural. Except for adjectives referring to masculine, animate nouns, the nominate and accusative plural are identical for all genders.

The basic endings (applying not only to adjectives, but also to possessive pronouns, demonstrative pronouns and the like) are: Singular Plural m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. -y (-i) -o (-e) -a acc. -ogo (-ego) -y (-i) -u gen. -ogo (-ego) -oj (-ej) dat. -omu (-emu) -oj (-ej) ins. -ym (-im) -oju (-eju) loc. -om (-em) -oj (-ej) m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. -i -e acc. -yh (-ih) gen. -yh (-ih) dat. -ym (-im) ins. -ymi (-imi) loc. -yh (-ih)

Example of the declension of hard adjectives: dobry ‚Äûgood‚Äù: Singular Plural m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. dobry dobro dobra acc. dobrogo dobry dobru gen. dobrogo dobroj dat. dobromu dobroj ins. dobrym dobroju loc. dobrom dobroj m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. dobri dobre acc. dobryh gen. dobryh dat. dobrym ins. dobrymi loc. dobryh

Example of the declension of soft adjectives: svƒõ≈æi ‚Äûfresh‚Äù: Singular Plural m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. svƒõ≈æi svƒõ≈æe svƒõ≈æa acc. svƒõ≈æego svƒõ≈æi svƒõ≈æu gen. svƒõ≈æego svƒõ≈æej dat. svƒõ≈æemu svƒõ≈æej ins. svƒõ≈æim svƒõ≈æeju loc. svƒõ≈æem svƒõ≈æej m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. svƒõ≈æi svƒõ≈æe acc. svƒõ≈æih gen. svƒõ≈æih dat. svƒõ≈æim ins. svƒõ≈æimi loc. svƒõ≈æih

A small number of adjectives exist in the so-called short form, a relic of the indefinite declension of adjectives in Common Slavic. This short form differs from regular adjectives only in the masculine nominative singular by omitting the ending -y/-i. The most common examples are the possessive adjectives -ov and -in, respecively expressing ownership by a masculine and feminine person: Petrov dom ‚ÄûPeter‚Äôs house‚Äù, materin stol ‚Äûmother‚Äôs table‚Äù. All other forms are regular: Petrova kniga ‚ÄûPeter‚Äôs book‚Äù, na materinom stolu ‚Äûon mother‚Äôs table‚Äù. These possessive adjectives are only used when the possessor is a single word. In other cases, the genitive is used: bratova kniga ‚Äûbrother‚Äôs book‚Äù, but: kniga mojego brata ‚Äûmy brother‚Äôs book‚Äù; Pu≈°kinova poezija ‚ÄûPushkin‚Äôs poetry‚Äù, but: poezija Aleksandra Pu≈°kina ‚ÄûAleksandr Pushkin‚Äôs poetry‚Äù. The short form may also be used when the adjective forms the predicate of the sentence: Petr jest ≈°ƒçestliv ‚ÄûPeter is happy‚Äù, dom jest velik ‚Äûthe house is big‚Äù, etc. This is not mandatory though, and in most cases, people will simply write: Petr jest ≈°ƒçestlivy and dom jest veliky.
Adverbs can be derived from adjectives by using the ending -o (-e after a soft consonant). In other words, they are identical to the neuter singular: dobro ‚Äûwell‚Äù, svƒõ≈æe ‚Äûfreshly‚Äù.
Comparatives and superlatives can be built in two ways: a simple (analytic) form and a more complex (synthetic) form.

This way of forming a comparative is easiest to use. Simply have the ground form (the positive) of an adjective or adverb preceded by vy≈°e or bolje ‚Äûmore‚Äù: vy≈°e prosty ‚Äûmore simple = simpler‚Äù. This solution can be used for all adjectives and adverbs, but is most likely encountered in the case of very long words, foreign words, and participles: vy≈°e/bolje sintetiƒçny ‚Äûmore synthetic‚Äù, vy≈°e/bolje smrdeƒçi ‚Äûmore stinking‚Äù.

The basic comparative ending for adjectives -ƒõj≈°i (-ej≈°i after a soft consonant), replacing the ending -y/-i: bogaty ‚Üí bogatƒõj≈°i, slaby ‚Üí slabƒõj≈°i, blagy ‚Üí bla≈æej≈°i, svƒõ≈æi ‚Üí svƒõ≈æej≈°i. These endings can simply be made into adverbs by replacing the element -≈°i by -e (giving the ending -ƒõje/-eje instead of the adverbial ending -o/-e): novo ‚Üí novƒõje, ƒçisto ‚Üí ƒçistƒõje, tiho ‚Üí ti≈°eje, svƒõ≈æe ‚Üí svƒõ≈æeje. An exception are adjectives on -ky, -eky, -oky, which have -≈°i instead: kratky ‚Üí krat≈°i, tenky ‚Üí ten≈°i, daleky ‚Üí dal≈°i, vysoky ‚Üí vys≈°i. The comparatives of these adjectives can be adverbialised by adding the ending -je to the root, causing iotation of the preceding consonant(s): daleko ‚Üí dalje, ≈°iroko ‚Üí ≈°irje, vysoky ‚Üí vy≈°e, blizko ‚Üí bli≈æe, rƒõdko ‚Üí rƒõd≈æe.

Seven adjectives have an irregular comparative: dobry ‚Äûgood‚Äù ‚Üí lƒõp≈°i (adv. lƒõpje) or luƒç≈°i (adv. luƒç≈°e) ‚Äûbetter‚Äù zly ‚Äûbad‚Äù ‚Üí gor≈°i (adv. gorje) ‚Äûworse‚Äù veliky ‚Äûbig, large‚Äù ‚Üí veƒç≈°i (adv. veƒçe) or bol≈°i (adv. bolje) ‚Äûbigger, larger‚Äù maly ‚Äûlittle, small‚Äù ‚Üí men≈°i (adv. menje) ‚Äûsmaller, less‚Äù blagy ‚Äûpleasant, joyful‚Äù ‚Üí un≈°i (adv. unje) ‚Äûmore pleasant/joyful‚Äù legky ‚Äûeasy, light‚Äù ‚Üí leg≈°i (adv. leg≈°e) ‚Äûeasier, lighter‚Äù mekky ‚Äûsoft‚Äù ‚Üí mek≈°i (adv. mek≈°e) ‚Äûsofter‚Äù It is not impossible to use regular forms of these adjectives (like dobrƒõj≈°i or zlƒõj≈°i), but to the average Slav this will look childish or artificial.

The superlative is formed by adding the prefix naj- to the comparative: najnovƒõj≈°i (adj.), najnovƒõje (adv.). This works for the analytic comparative, too: najvy≈°e sintetiƒçny or najbolje sintetiƒçny. As a means of simplification, this prefix can also be added to the positive instead (which is how superlatives are made in Bulgarian and Macedonian): najnovy (adj.), najnovo (adv.).

The adverbs menje and najmenje can be used to express the opposite meaning of vy≈°e/bolje and najvy≈°e/najbolje, meaning ‚Äûless‚Äù and ‚Äûleast‚Äù respectively. The prefix prƒõ- attached to the positive can be used as a kind of superlative as well, expressing an extreme or excessive degree (‚Äûvery‚Äù, ‚Äûtoo‚Äù). The prefix ne- creates a negative: neprijetny ‚Äûnot pleasant, unpleasant‚Äù.

prosty ‚Äûsimple‚Äù (adjective, positive) prosto ‚Äûsimply‚Äù (adverb, positive) prostƒõj≈°i ‚Äûsimpler‚Äù or vy≈°e prosty or bolje prosty ‚Äûmore simple, simpler‚Äù prostƒõje ‚Äûsimplier‚Äù or vy≈°e prosto or bolje prosto ‚Äûmore simply, simplier‚Äù najprostƒõj≈°i or najprosty or najvy≈°e prosty or najbolje prosty ‚Äûsimplest‚Äù najprostƒõje or najprosto or najvy≈°e prosto or najbolje prosto ‚Äûsimpliest, most simply‚Äù menje prosty ‚Äûless simple‚Äù menje prosto ‚Äûless simply‚Äù najmenje prosty ‚Äûleast simple‚Äù najmenje prosto ‚Äûleast simply‚Äù neprosty ‚Äûnot simple‚Äù prƒõprosty ‚Äûtoo simple, overly simple, extremely simple‚Äù Legal information This article has been republished with the permission of its original author, Jan van Steenbergen.

Most prepositions in Interslavic govern the genitive. This is especially true for all prepositions that were derived from nouns, adjectives or adverbs. In the case of prepositions referring to place and time, the following can be assumed as a guideline, although there are exceptions: the genitive case is used when a movement away from/out of a location is indicated. the accusative case is used when a movement towards/into a location is indicated; the instrumental or locative case is used when the location is stable, i.e. there is no movement at all. Prepositions should only be used according to their logical meaning, not according to national idioms. Here follows a list of prepositions in Interslavic:

bez ‚Äì without blizko ‚Äì near, close to dlja ‚Äì for do ‚Äì to, towards, till iz ‚Äì from, out of iz-med≈æu ‚Äì from between iz-nad ‚Äì from above iz-pod ‚Äì from under iz-prƒõd ‚Äì from before iz-srƒõd ‚Äì from among iz-za ‚Äì from behind kolo ‚Äì next to, around kromƒõ ‚Äì except mimo ‚Äì past, by naprotiv ‚Äì opposite od ‚Äì of, from (away from); since; by (agent) odnosno ‚Äì concering, about okolo ‚Äì around; about, approximately podƒças ‚Äì during, so long as podle ‚Äì near, beside pomimo ‚Äì in spite of poprƒõk ‚Äì across pored ‚Äì next to poslƒõ ‚Äì after posrƒõd ‚Äì amidst, in the middle of, among posrƒõdstvom ‚Äì by means of, using povrh ‚Äì to the upper side of, atop srƒõd ‚Äì among, amid suprotiv ‚Äì contrary to u ‚Äì at, at the place of vdol≈æ ‚Äì along vmƒõsto ‚Äì instead of vnƒõ ‚Äì outside of vnutri ‚Äì inside, within vslƒõd ‚Äì following, because of, as a result of za ‚Äì during, in times of

blagodare, dekujuƒçi, hvala ‚Äì thanks to k ‚Äì to, towards (direction) po ‚Äì according to, per, by, in the manner of; for ... each, for ... a * piece protiv ‚Äì against soglasno, suglasno ‚Äì according to
ƒçrƒõz, prƒõz ‚Äì through, across, via po ‚Äì for (in pursuit of, to get something); for (the Xth time); up to za ‚Äì for, because of, due to, in exchange for, in favour of, instead of
ponad ‚Äì above, beyond s, so ‚Äì with, together with; by means of, using
o, ob ‚Äì about; concerning, regarding po ‚Äì after, following; along(side); throughout, round, all over pri ‚Äì near; during (rule of a king)

The following five prepositions refer to place and (if applicable) time. The instrumental is used when the location is stable (Kot spi pod stolom ‚Äì "The cat is sleeping under the table"), the accusative expresses a motion toward it (Kot pobƒõgl pod stol ‚Äì "The cat fled under the table"). The preposition za can also be used with the genitive and (in other meanings) the accusative, but because otherwise it belongs to the same category as the rest, it has been listed there separately. med≈æu ‚Äì between (place & time) nad ‚Äì above, over, beyond pod ‚Äì under prƒõd ‚Äì before, in front of, ahead of (place & time), prior to, ago za ‚Äì behind (place), after (time)
documents.s: With the accusative and the instrumental

documents.t: The prepositions v and na behave exactly like the previous category, except that for a stable location the locative is used instead of the instrumental. na (+ loc.) ‚Äì on, at; (+ acc.) ‚Äì on(to), unto v, vo (+ loc.) ‚Äì in, within; (+ acc.) ‚Äì into
documents.s: With the accusative and the locative

documents.t: The following combinations are no real prepositions, but are used as such and are often translated as prepositions. The list is of course far from being exhaustive. bez obzira na (acc.) ‚Äì regardless ƒçto se tyƒçe (gen.) ‚Äì regarding, with regard to na prƒõkor (gen.) ‚Äì in defiance of ne gledajuƒçi na (acc.) ‚Äì disregarding, despite, in spite of, * notwithstanding od strany (gen.) ‚Äì by, on the part of po odno≈°enju k (dat.) ‚Äì regarding, with regard to pod vodstvom (gen.) ‚Äì under the leadership of s izkljuƒçenjem (gen.) ‚Äì except, with the exception of s obzirom na (acc.) ‚Äì with regard to s pomoƒçju (gen.) ‚Äì with the help of sgodno s (ins.) ‚Äì conform susedno do (gen.) ‚Äì next to, neighbouring to v ƒçasu (gen.) ‚Äì during v imenu (gen.) ‚Äì in the name of v obliƒçju (gen.) ‚Äì in the face of v odrazlikƒõ od (gen.) ‚Äì unlike, in contrast to v odno≈°enju k (dat.) ‚Äì regarding, with regard to v ramah, v ramkah (gen.) ‚Äì within the framework of, as a part of v protivnosti k (dat.) ‚Äì unlike, in opposition to v smyslu (gen.) ‚Äì in the sense of v razliƒçju od (gen.) ‚Äì unlike v svezi s (ins.) ‚Äì in connection with v tƒõƒçenju (gen.) ‚Äì during v vrƒõmenu (gen.) ‚Äì during v zamƒõn za (acc.) ‚Äì instead of, in exchange for Many prepositions can also be used as prefixes. See word formation for details. Legal information This article has been republished with the permission of its original author, Jan van Steenbergen.

Like most Slavic languages, nouns in Interslavic have three grammatical genders (masculine, feminine, neuter), two numbers (singular, plural) and seven cases (nominative, accusative, genitive, dative, instrumental, locative, vocative). The vocative, used for addressing a person or object directly, is actually not a real case, as it behaves significantly different from other cases: it exists only in the singular of masculine and feminine nouns, it never affects adjectives or pronouns, and it has nothing to do with the syntactic structure of the sentence. Long and complicated paradigms are to be avoided, but we cannot escape distinguishing between a few different word classes. Basically, Interslavic has three declensions: The first declension includes all masculine nouns ending in a consonant, as well as neuter nouns ending in -o or -e. The second declension includes all feminine nouns on -a. The third declension all feminine nouns on a consonant. An optional fourth (‚Äûathematic‚Äù) declension is discussed below. Within the first declension, we distinguish between three types. This difference affects only the nominative, the accusative and the vocative: Masculine animate (animals and male persons): the accusative is always identical to the genitive Masculine inanimate (all remaining masculine nouns): the accusative is always identical to the nominative Neuter: the nominative, accusative and vocative are always identical Another distinction is made between hard and soft declension patterns. Soft stems are stems ending in ≈°, ≈æ, ƒç, c, j, lj or nj. As a rule, after a soft stem the -o and -y of the ending become -e, the -ƒõ becomes -i. The basic endings are displayed in the tables below. The forms between brackets are used after soft stems. Zero endings are marked with -√ò: Singular Plural I declension II III m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. -√ò -o (-e) -a -√ò acc. -a -√ò -u gen. -a -y (-e) -i dat. -u -ƒõ (-i) -i ins. -om (-em) -oju (-eju) -ju loc. -u -ƒõ (-i) -i voc. -e (-u) -o (-e) -o -i I declension II III m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. -i -y (-e) -a -y (-e) -i acc. -ov (-ev) gen. -ov (-ev) -√ò -√ò -ij dat. -am ins. -ami loc. -ah In the dictionary, only the gender of words is given. For that reason the examples below are grouped by gender and not by declension.

Virtually all masculine nouns end in a consonant. Basically, there is only one declensional pattern for masculine nouns, but a few things need to be remembered: In the case of animate nouns (animals and male persons) the accusative is always identical to the genitive, while in the case of inanimate objects the accusative is identical to the nominative. After a soft consonant, the endings -om, -ov and -y are changed to -em, -ev, -e. Animate nouns have the nominative plural ending -i instead of the ending -y/-e of inanimate nouns. Four examples: brat ‚Äûbrother‚Äù, dom ‚Äûhouse‚Äù, mu≈æ ‚Äûman‚Äù, kraj ‚Äûcountry‚Äù. animate (hard) animate (soft) inanimate (hard) inanimate (soft) sg. pl. nom. brat brati acc. brata bratov gen. brata bratov dat. bratu bratam ins. bratom bratami loc. bratu bratah voc. brate brati sg. pl. nom. mu≈æ mu≈æi acc. mu≈æa mu≈æev gen. mu≈æa mu≈æev dat. mu≈æu mu≈æam ins. mu≈æem mu≈æami loc. mu≈æu mu≈æah voc. mu≈æu mu≈æi sg. pl. nom. dom domy acc. dom domy gen. doma domov dat. domu domam ins. domom domami loc. domu domah voc. dome domy sg. pl. nom. kraj kraje acc. kraj kraje gen. kraja krajev dat. kraju krajam ins. krajem krajami loc. kraju krajah voc. kraju kraje Notes The locative singular is where the Slavic languages differ most. The recommended ending is -u (i.e. the same as the dative), which in most languages occurs at least in some instances. Alternatively, it is also possible to use -ƒõ after hard consonants and -i after soft consonants (e.g. bratƒõ, mu≈æi). In the vocative, k, g and h become ƒç, ≈æ and ≈° before e: ƒçlovƒõk ‚Üí ƒçlovƒõƒçe, Bog ‚Üí Bo≈æe. Words on -ec have the vocative ending -ƒçe instead of the expected -cu: otec ‚Üí otƒçe. Some nouns ending in a hard consonant have a soft consonant in scientific orthography, e.g. gos≈• ‚Äûguest‚Äù, lƒõka≈ï ‚Äûdoctor, physician‚Äù. They can follow both the hard and the soft declension pattern: gen.pl. gostov or gostev. Words on -anin lose the morpheme -in- in the plural: nom.sg. Slovjanin, gen.sg. Slovjanina, but: nom.pl. Slovjani, gen.pl. Slovjanov. There are a few words on -a denoting male persons, such as sluga ‚Äûservant‚Äù, kolega ‚Äûcolleague‚Äù, sudja ‚Äûjudge‚Äù, etc. In the plural these are inflected like brat or mu≈æ, but in the singular, they follow the pattern of the second declension.

Neuter nouns end in -o (hard stems) or -e (soft stems). Except for the nominative/accusative and the genitive plural, their inflection is identical to that of inanimate masculine nouns. Please note: The accusative is always identical to the nominative. The nominative/accusative and instrumental singular are affected by the o/e rule. As for the locative singular, what goes for masculine nouns goes also for neuter nouns: instead of -u, it is also possible to write -ƒõ after a hard consonant or -i after a soft consonant. Neuter nouns do not have a vocative separate from the nominative. In the genitive plural, neuter nouns of the first declension have a zero ending -√ò. In cases when this leads to impossible consonant clusters, an -e- is inserted before -j or after a soft consonant, or an -o- between hard consonants: okno ‚Üí okon, morje ‚Üí morej. There is also special group of neuter nouns with the ending -e (in scientific orthography: -ƒô), for example ime ‚Äûname‚Äù (stem: imen-) and tele ‚Äûcalf‚Äù (stem: telƒôt-). It also includes a few words on -o, for example nebo ‚Äûheaven‚Äù (stem: nebes-). In Old Church Slavonic they belonged to a special declension, which nowadays has vanished in most languages. They can be inflected as ordinary neuter nouns (as if their nominatives were imeno and teleto), they can also be declined according to the more archaic athematic declension. Because we usually do not distinguish between ƒô and e, it is useful to remember that a noun ending in -e is always neuter, and as a rule of thumb, when this -e is preceded by: m, then the root is -men-: ime, gen. imena a hard consonant, then the root is -et-: tele, gen. teleta (noun of this group usually refer to children or young animals) a soft consonant, then the root is -√ò-: morje, pl. morja (in other words, an -o noun affected by the o/e rule) For the rest, declension is always regular. Three examples: slovo ‚Äûword‚Äù, morje ‚Äûsea‚Äù, ime ‚Äûname‚Äù. hard soft ƒô (—ß) sg. pl. nom. slovo slova acc. slovo slova gen. slova slov dat. slovu slovam ins. slovom slovami loc. slovu slovah voc. slovo slova sg. pl. nom. morje morja acc. morje morja gen. morja morej dat. morju morjam ins. morjem morjami loc. morju morjah voc. morje morja sg. pl. nom. ime imena acc. ime imena gen. imene imen dat. imeni imenam ins. imenem imenami loc. imeni imenah voc. ime imena

Most feminine nouns have the ending -a and therefore belong to the second declension. Again, we distinguish between hard and soft stems. In the case of feminine nouns the differences between hard and soft declension are not merely a matter of applying the o/e rule. As a rule, the endings -y and -ƒõ after a hard consonant become -e and -i after a soft consonant (in other words, they are ‚Äûreversed‚Äù). Just like in the case of neuter nouns, the zero ending in the genitive plural may require the insertion of a epenthetic vowel -e- or -o-. A few words on -i belong to this group as well (for example pani, which is inflected as if the nominative singular were *panja). The -a declension also includes a number of masculine nouns with the ending -a referring to male persons, like sluga ‚Äûservant‚Äù and sudja ‚Äûjudge‚Äù. They are inflected like ≈æena or zemja in the singular, but in the plural they follow the pattern of masculine animate nouns: nom.sg. sluga, gen.sg. slugy, nom.pl. slugi, gen.pl. slugov, etc. Another group of feminine nouns are those ending in a consonant. They form the third declension. Most nouns of this category end in -ost. Examples: ≈æena ‚Äûwoman‚Äù, zemja ‚Äûearth‚Äù, kost ‚Äûbone‚Äù. II declension (hard) II declension (soft) III declension sg. pl. nom. ≈æena ≈æeny acc. ≈æenu ≈æeny gen. ≈æeny ≈æen dat. ≈æenƒõ ≈æenam ins. ≈æenoju ≈æenami loc. ≈æenƒõ ≈æenah voc. ≈æeno ≈æeny sg. pl. nom. zemja zemje acc. zemju zemje gen. zemje zemej dat. zemji zemjam ins. zemjeju zemjami loc. zemji zemjah voc. zemjo zemje sg. pl. nom. kost kosti acc. kost kosti gen. kosti kostij dat. kosti kostam ins. kostju kostami loc. kosti kostah voc. kosti kosti

Except for the regular declensions listed above, Old Church Slavonic also had another declension type, the so-called athematic declension. Nouns of this type have gone various ways in the modern Slavic languages, mostly merging into one or more of the regular declension types. Interslavic projects choose various approaches to this group, but some of them preserve it. This declension type includes nouns of all three genders, but most numerous among them are neuter nouns. The following subtypes can be distinguished: masculine nouns on -en, a tiny group including e.g. kamen ‚Äûstone‚Äù and koren ‚Äûroot‚Äù neuter nouns on -me/-men-, containing numerous nouns like ime ‚Äûname‚Äù, rame ‚Äûshoulder‚Äù, brƒõme ‚Äûburden‚Äù neuter nouns on -e/-et-, referring to children and young animals, e.g. tele ‚Äûcalf‚Äù, prase ‚Äûpiglet‚Äù neuter nouns on -o/-es-, a group of only a few words, e.g. nebo ‚Äûheaven‚Äù feminine nouns on -ov, e.g. crkov ‚Äûchurch‚Äù, mrkov ‚Äûcarrot‚Äù feminine nouns on -i/-er-, containing only two nouns: mati ‚Äûmother‚Äù and doƒçi ‚Äûdaughter‚Äù m. (‚Äëen‚Äë) n. (‚Äëmen‚Äë) n. (‚Äëet‚Äë) n. (‚Äëes‚Äë) f. (‚Äëv‚Äë) f. (‚Äër‚Äë) sg. pl. nom. kamen kameni acc. kamen kameni gen. kamene kamenev dat. kameni kamenam ins. kamenem kamenami loc. kameni kamenah voc. kamen kameni sg. pl. nom. ime imena acc. ime imena gen. imene imen dat. imeni imenam ins. imenem imenami loc. imeni imenah voc. ime imena sg. pl. nom. tele teleta acc. tele teleta gen. telete telet dat. teleti teletam ins. teletem teletami loc. teleti teletah voc. tele teleta sg. pl. nom. nebo nebesa acc. nebo nebesa gen. nebese nebes dat. nebesi nebesam ins. nebesem nebesami loc. nebesi nebesah voc. nebo nebesa sg. pl. nom. crkov crkvi acc. crkov crkvi gen. crkve crkvij dat. crkvi crkvam ins. crkovju crkvami loc. crkvi crkvah voc. crkov crkvi sg. pl. nom. mati materi acc. mati materi gen. matere materij dat. materi materam ins. materju materami loc. materi materah voc. mati materi The entire athematic declension can be avoided by inflecting these words according to the regular declensions, as most other Slavic languages do. In that case: kamenj is inflected like an ordinary masculine noun (gen. kamenja, dat. kamenju) ime and tele are inflected like slovo, as if their nominatives were imeno and teleto: gen. imena, teleta, dat. imenu, teletu nebo is inflected like slovo too (gen. neba, dat. nebu) crkov is inflected like kost (gen. crkvi); instead of crkov, it is also possible to use the form crkva, which is inflected lke ≈æena (gen. crkvy, dat. crkvƒõ) mati is inflected like kost: gen./dat. materi

Interslavic is kept as regular as possible, but a few cases of irregularity cannot be avoided without defying naturalism. The following nouns have an irregular plural (all four inflected like a feminine noun of the kost type): ƒçlovƒõk (m.) ‚Äûhuman being, person‚Äù, pl. ljudi ‚Äûpeople‚Äù dƒõte (gen. dƒõteta or dƒõtete) (n.) ‚Äûchild‚Äù, pl. dƒõti ‚Äûchildren‚Äù oko (n.) ‚Äûeye‚Äù, pl. oƒçi ‚Äûeyes‚Äù uho (n.) ‚Äûear‚Äù, pl. u≈°i ‚Äûears‚Äù Regular plurals (ƒçlovƒõki, oka etc.) can be used as well, but some of them sound very strange to the Slavic ear, even though they will be understood anyway.

Borrowed international vocabulary ending in -e, -i or -u (e.g. alibi, hobi, intervju, kafe, kakao, kli≈°e, menju, tabu, taksi) and abbreviations are indeclinable. It is not impossible to add case endings anyway, but in that case, it is best to separate them from the noun with an apostrophe: togo alibi‚Äôa, te intervju‚Äôy, tyh taksi‚Äôov, etc. Legal information This article has been republished with the permission of its original author, Jan van Steenbergen.

There is little that can be said to introduce the cardinal numbers, so let's move on to the forms: The numbers 0-10 are: 0. nula, 1. jedin (jedna, jedno), 2. dva (dvƒõ), 3. tri, 4. ƒçetyri, 5. pet, 6. ≈°est, 7. sedm, 8. osm, 9. devet, 10. deset. The -teens (11-19) are formed by adding -nadset (pronounced -nacet) to the numbers 1-9: 11. jedinnadset, 12. dvanadset, 13. trinadset, 14. ƒçetyrinadset, 15. petnadset, 16. ≈°estnadset, 17. sedmnadset, 18. osmnadset, 19. devetnadset. The ‚Äû-ties‚Äù (20-90) are formed by adding -deset to the numbers 2-9: 20. dvadeset, 30. trideset, 40. ƒçetyrideset, 50. petdeset, 60. ≈°estdeset, 70. sedmdeset, 80. osmdeset, 90. devetdeset. The hundreds (100-900) are formed by adding -sto to the numbers 2-9: 100. sto, 200. dvasto, 300. tristo, 400. ƒçetyristo, 500. petsto, 600. ≈°eststo, 700. sedmsto, 800. osmsto, 900. devetsto Alternatively, the hundreds can also be formed by inflecting the word sto, resulting in the following set: 100. sto, 200. dvƒõstƒõ, 300. trista, 400. ƒçetyrista, 500. petsot, 600. ≈°estsot, 700. sedmsot, 800. osmsot, 900. devetsot. The words for ‚Äûthousand‚Äù, ‚Äûmillion‚Äù and ‚Äûmilliard‚Äù are: tyseƒç (1000), milion (10‚Å∂) and miliard (10‚Åπ). Just like in the case of the hundreds, these words may or may not be inflected as nouns. Although it is not customary in the Slavic languages to do this, in cases like pet-tyseƒá ‚Äû5000‚Äù a hyphen may be added for clarity. Combinations of these are always made from high to low: thousands ‚Äì hundreds ‚Äì tens ‚Äì ones. Between the tens and the ones, the word i ‚Äûand‚Äù may be inserted. For example: tri-tyseƒç ƒçetyristo petdeset (i) ≈°est` ‚Äû3,456‚Äù. Because the primary purpose of Interslavic is to be maximally understood by Slavic speakers, it deserves recommendation to write digits instead of number words. For the average Westerner it would make most sense if the word jedin were followed by a noun in the singular, and all the remaining numerals by a noun in the plural: jedin dom, dva domy, pet domy, dvadeset domy, milion domy. However, in the Slavic languages things work differently. All numbers higher than 4 are followed by the genitive plural: pet domov (lit. ‚Äûfive of houses‚Äù). In the case of the numbers 2-4, most languages use the nominative plural in most cases, but some languages, notably Serbo-Croat and Russian, prefer the genitive singular instead. For reasons of clarity, however, it is recommended to use the nominative singular after 1, the nominative plural after 2-4 and the genitive plural after 5 and more: jedin dom, dva domy, ƒçetyri domy, pet domov.

The easiest solution for the declension of cardinal numbers is simply not to decline them at all. Dom s tri eta≈æami ‚ÄûA house with three floors‚Äù is perfectly understandable, even though it may sound a little strange to native speakers. However, a better effect can be achieved by using the following declension patterns: 1‚Äã Except for the masculine nominative singular, the word jedin ‚Äûone‚Äù is declined like an adjective *jedny: m. jedin, jednogo, f. jedna, jednoj, n. jedno, etc. In some cases, it can also be used in the plural: Jedni ljudi prƒõdpoƒçitajut lƒõto, drugi zimu ‚ÄûSome people prefer Summer, others Winter‚Äù. This is also the case for pluralia tantum: jedne dveri ‚Äûone door‚Äù. 2-4‚Äã These numbers are declined in a somewhat unfamiliar way, because their patterns show remnants of the ancient dual. Only dva ‚Äûtwo‚Äù has gender distinction, albeit only in the nominative/accusative. 2 3 4 masculine feminine nom. dva dvƒõ tri ƒçetyri acc. gen. dvoh trƒõh ƒçetyrƒõh dat. dvom trƒõm ƒçetyrƒõm ins. dvoma trƒõmi ƒçetyrƒõmi loc. dvoh trƒõh ƒçetyrƒõh The neuter of "2" is dva in Russian, Belarussian, Ukrainian, Polish, Cashubian and Serbocroat, dvƒõ in Old Church Slavonic, Czech, Slovak, Upper and Lower Sorbian, Slovene, Macedonian, Bulgarian and Rusyn. In Interslavic, both options are equally valid. Also declined like dva are the words oba and obydva ‚Äûboth‚Äù, ‚Äûthe two of‚Äù. 5-99‚Äã The numbers pet and up are inflected like nouns of the pattern kost. The subject always remains in the genitive plural. Examples: 5 12 30 nom. pet dvanadset trideset acc. gen. peti dvanadseti trideseti dat. peti dvanadseti trideseti ins. petju dvanadsetju tridesetju loc. peti dvanadseti trideseti 0, 100, 1000, 106, 109‚Äã The remaining numbers are declined as nouns, too: nula ‚Äûzero‚Äù as a feminine noun (like ≈æena), sto ‚Äûhundred‚Äù as a neuter noun (like slovo), tyseƒç ‚Äûthousand‚Äù as a masculine or a feminine noun (gen. tyseƒça or tyseƒçi), milion ‚Äûmillion‚Äù and miliard ‚Äûmilliard‚Äù (or ‚Äûbillion‚Äù) as masculine nouns.

Apart from the quantitative numbers listed above, there is also a category of so-called indefinite cardinal numbers, consisting of words like mnogo ‚Äûmuch, many‚Äù, malo ‚Äûlittle, few‚Äù, velje ‚Äûa lot‚Äù, veƒçe ‚Äûmore‚Äù, menje ‚Äûless‚Äù, koliko ‚Äûhow many‚Äù, nƒõkoliko ‚Äûa few, some‚Äù, toliko ‚Äûthis/that many‚Äù, para ‚Äûa few‚Äù.

Ordinal numbers, roughly speaking, refer to the place of an item in a row. In terms of grammar, these words are adjectives, and just like ordinary adjectives, they match with the noun they modify in gender, case and number. All ordinal numerals are inflected like adjectives with a hard stem (like dobry), except for trƒõtji, which follows the soft declension (like svƒõ≈æi). The ordinal numbers 1-4 are: prvy ‚Äûfirst‚Äù, drugy or vtory ‚Äûsecond‚Äù, trƒõtji ‚Äûthird‚Äù and ƒçetvrty ‚Äûfourth‚Äù. The remaining ordinals, up to 99, are formed by adding the ending -y to the cardinal numbers: pety ‚Äû5th‚Äù, ≈°esty ‚Äû6th‚Äù, sedmy ‚Äû7th‚Äù, osmy ‚Äû8th‚Äù, devety ‚Äû9th‚Äù, desety ‚Äû10th‚Äù; jedinnadsety ‚Äû11th‚Äù, dvadesety ‚Äû20th‚Äù, etc. The word for ‚Äû100th‚Äù is sotny or stoty, the word for ‚Äû1000th‚Äù is tyseƒçny. When a higher number forms a string, only the last member is modified to create an ordinal number: v tyseƒç devetsot osmdeset ƒçetvrtom godu ‚Äûin the year 1984‚Äù.

Most Slavic languages use the ordinal numbers for fractions: dvƒõ trƒõtje ‚Äûtwo thirds, 2/3‚Äù. However, for reasons of clarity if would deserve recommendation to use the following, universally understandable forms instead: The word for ‚Äûhalf‚Äù is pol (polovina, polovica). It can also be used as a prefix: pol-mrtvy ‚Äûhalf-dead‚Äù. All other forms are built by substituting the ending -y of ordinal numbers to -ina: tretjina ‚Äû1/3‚Äù, ƒçetvrtina ‚Äû1/4‚Äù, petina ‚Äû1/5‚Äù, ≈°estina ‚Äû1/6‚Äù, sedmina ‚Äû1/7‚Äù, osmina ‚Äû1/8‚Äù, devetina ‚Äû1/9‚Äù, desetina ‚Äû1/10‚Äù. This works also for higher numbers: ≈°estnadsetina ‚Äû1/16‚Äù, sotina or stotina ‚Äû1/100‚Äù. They are inflected as feminine nouns. Thus, ‚Äû7/38‚Äù is represented as sedm trideseti-osmin (the hyphen is meant to enhance clarity).

The cardinal and ordinal numbers are by far the most significant. However, the Slavic languages have other categories as well. Most of them are rarely used nowadays, or used only under particular circumstances, but they should be mentioned anyway for reasons of completeness. The collective numbers refer to members a closed group, and can be translated as ‚Äûa group of‚Äù, ‚Äû-some‚Äù. The forms are: dvoje ‚Äûtwosome, pair‚Äù, troje ‚Äûthreesome, a group of three‚Äù, ƒçetvero, petero, ≈°estero, sedmero, osmero, devetero, desetero. This group also includes oboje ‚Äûboth‚Äù. It can be used instead of a cardinal number in the following cases: when the group consists of both men and women: dva studenti ‚Äûtwo students (m.)‚Äù, dvƒõ studentky ‚Äûtwo students (f.)‚Äù, dvoje studentov ‚Äûtwo students (m. + f.)‚Äù with gender-neutral words like ljudi and dƒõti: osmero ljudij ‚Äûeight people‚Äù, ƒçetvero dƒõtij ‚Äûfour children‚Äù with neuter words denoting young animals (sg. -e, pl. -eta): troje telet ‚Äûthree calves‚Äù for objects that naturally come in pairs, for example: dvoje r≈≥kavic ‚Äûtwo gloves‚Äù with words that exist only in the plural (pluralia tantum): dvoje dverij ‚Äûtwo doors‚Äù. As can be seen from these examples, the noun following a collective numeral is always in the genitive plural, and if this noun is the subject of a sentence, the corresponding verb is in the 3rd person singular (neuter). Collective numbers can also be used without a noun, in cases like: my oboje ‚Äûboth of us (m. + f.)‚Äù, zabava v troje ‚Äûa party for three‚Äù.

The stems of the collective numerals can also be used as the base for multiplicative (or aggregative) adjectives: dvojny ‚Äûdouble, twofold‚Äù, trojny ‚Äûtreble, triple, threefold‚Äù, ƒçetverny ‚Äûquadruple, fourfold‚Äù. Less frequent, but not impossible, are higher numbers: peterny ‚Äûquintuple‚Äù, ≈°esterny ‚Äûsextuple‚Äù, etc. To the same family also belongs jediny ‚Äûonly, single‚Äù. With the prefix po-, these adjectives can also be turned into verbs: podvojiti ‚Äûto double‚Äù, potrojiti ‚Äûto triple‚Äù, poƒçetveriti ‚Äûto multiply by four‚Äù. The opposite can be achieved with the prefix raz-: razdvojiti ‚Äûto split in two‚Äù, raztrojiti ‚Äûto separate into three parts‚Äù. Another type of multiplicative numerals are adverbs, formed by adding the suffix -kratno to the cardinal number: jednokratno ‚Äûonce, one time‚Äù, dvakratno ‚Äûtwice, two times‚Äù, trikratno ‚Äûthrice, three times‚Äù, etc. This suffix can be used for indefinite numbers as well: mnogokratno ‚Äûmany times‚Äù, nƒõkolikokratno ‚Äûa few times‚Äù.

Yet another group of numeral-based adjectives are the differential (qualitative, generic) numbers. They refer to a qualitative differentation of the items in question, and can be translated as ‚Äûdifferent types of‚Äù. An old form (based again on the collective numbers) is dvoj, troj (declined like the possessive pronoun moj). However, more common and less confusing has the ending -aky: dvojaky, trojaky, ƒçetveraky, peteraky, etc.: dvojake knigy ‚Äûtwo kinds of books‚Äù. This works also for indefinite numbers: kolikoraky ‚Äûhow many sorts of‚Äù. When adverbialised, the meaning becomes something like ‚Äûin X ways‚Äù: trojako ‚Äûin three ways‚Äù.

Sometimes numbers are used as substantives, for example when we refer to a drawing or sculpture of a number, a bus, a radio or TV channel, a mark given in school, a banknote or a playing card. It can simply be translated as ‚Äûa three‚Äù, ‚Äûthe five‚Äù, etc. In the case of the numbers 2-4, this is done by adding the ending -ka to the collective numeral stem, in the remaining cases to the cardinal number: jedinka, dvojka, trojka, ƒçetverka, petka, ≈°estka, etc. Alternatively, the ending -ica can be used, too, but this does not work in all cases: jedinica, petica, ≈°estica, sedmica etc.

A somewhat special case is presented by the number of children from a birth: twins, triplets, quadruplets, quintuplets, etc.. The Slavic languages have different ways of expressing this: East Slavic: -ne (pl. -neta) ‚Äì dvojne, trojne, ƒçetverne, peterne (1 of 2, 3, 4, 5) Czecho-Slovak: -ƒçe (pl. -ƒçeta) - dvojƒçe, trojƒçe, ƒçetverƒçe, peterƒçe Polish: -ak - dvojak, trojak, ƒçetverak, peterak Slovene: -ƒçek ‚Äì dvojƒçek, trojƒçek, ƒçetverƒçek, peterƒçek South Slavic: -ka - dvojka, trojka, ƒçetverka, peterka Legal information This article has been republished with the permission of its original author, Jan van Steenbergen.

A conjunction is a part of speech that connects two words, sentences, phrases or clauses together. Conjunctions are invariable and stand between the items they conjoin. There are three types of conjunctions: coordinating conjunctions join two or more items of equal syntactic importance, correlative conjunctions are conjunctions that work in pairs, and subordinate conjunctions link a dependent clause to an independent clause. ƒçim ... tym ... ‚Äûthe ... the ...‚Äù ili ... ili ... ‚Äûeither ... or ...‚Äù kako ... tako i ... ‚Äûboth ... and ...‚Äù koliko ... toliko ... ‚Äûthe ... the ...‚Äù ne jedino ... ale tako≈æe ‚Äûnot only ... but also ...‚Äù ni ... ni ... ‚Äûneither ... nor ...‚Äù

Personal pronouns have six cases‚Äîthe same as nouns but without the vocative. The reflexive pronoun sebe is inflected like ty, tebe, ‚Ä¶, the only difference being that it does not have a nominative. The forms between brackets are clitic forms, i.e., they are weaker and always unstressed. Se is used in reflexive verbs: Ja myju se ‚ÄûI'm washing myself‚Äù. If it needs to be stressed, the longer form is used: Ja myju jedino sebe ‚ÄûI wash nobody but myself‚Äù. After a preposition, it is better to use the longer forms: k mnƒõ, za tebe. Singular Plural Reflexive 1st person 2nd person 3rd person masc. neut. fem. nom. ja ty on ono ona acc. mene (me) tebe (te) jego (go) ju gen. mene tebe jego jej dat. mnƒõ (mi) tobƒõ (ti) jemu (mu) jej ins. mnoju toboju jim jeju loc. mnƒõ tobƒõ jim jej 1st person 2nd person 3rd person m.anim. other nom. my vy oni one acc. nas vas jih je gen. jih dat. nam vam jim ins. nami vami jimi loc. nas vas jih nom. ‚Äî acc. sebe (se) gen. sebe dat. sobƒõ (si) ins. soboju loc. sobƒõ Notes After a preposition, all pronouns of the third person are preceded by n-: jego > do njego; jim > pri njim, etc. (for that reason, the locative forms jim, jej and jih never occur, as the locative is always preceded by a preposition) If you are curious how these forms relate to the Slavic languages, you can see them compared here. A few more notes regarding usage: Because not all verb endings are equally obvious to all speakers of Slavic languages, pro-drop (i.e. omitting personal pronouns when they are the subject of a sentence) is not recommended. It is better to say ja ƒçitaju instead of just ƒçitaju, although the latter is definitely not incorrect. Prepositions can govern any case but the nominative, depending on their usage in the Slavic languages. The pronoun on refers to any noun of masculine gender and not only to male beings. In the same way, the pronoun ona refers to any noun of feminine gender and not only to female beings. As all natural Slavic languages, Interslavic has got T-V distinction, i.e. vy is a universal second person pronoun for both numbers, whereas the second person singular ty is used only for addressing friends, relatives and children. The reflexive pronoun can also be used as a reciprocal pronoun: Oni bijut se can mean ‚ÄûThey are hitting themselves‚Äù, but would rather have the meaning: ‚ÄûThey are hitting each other‚Äù. To be more explicit about the meaning ‚Äûeach other‚Äù, you can add the formula jedin drugogo:, e.g.: Oni bijut se jedin drugogo.

The possessive pronouns are inflected like adjectives, except for the zero ending in the masculine singular. The forms are: moj, moja, moje ‚Äûmy‚Äù tvoj, tvoja, tvoje ‚Äûyour, thy‚Äù na≈°, na≈°a, na≈°e ‚Äûour‚Äù va≈°, va≈°a, va≈°e ‚Äûyour (pl.)‚Äù svoj, svoja, svoje ‚Äûone's own‚Äù (reflexive) In the third person, it is most common to use the genitive of the corresponding personal pronoun: jego, jej, jih. These forms are not inflected. Alternatively, one can also use the following forms, which are declined like adjectives: jegov, jegova, jegovo ‚Äûhis‚Äù jejin, jejina, jejino ‚Äûher‚Äù jihny, jihna, jihno ‚Äûtheir‚Äù Whenever the possessor is also the subject of the sentence, the reflexive svoj is used, no matter whether this subject is in the third person or not: Ja myju svoje avto ‚ÄûI am washing my car‚Äù. Note the difference in meaning when the reflexive pronoun refers to a subject in the third person: Pjotr dal Ivanu svoju knigu ‚ÄûPjotr gave Ivan his [= Pjotr's] book‚Äù Pjotr dal Ivanu jegovu knigu ‚ÄûPjotr gave Ivan his [= Ivan's] book‚Äù. There are also interrogative, definite and indefinite possessive pronouns: ƒçij ‚Äûwhose‚Äù, niƒçij ‚Äûnobody's‚Äù, nƒõƒçij ‚Äûsomebody's‚Äù, etc. They are inflected like moj. For more forms, see the section about correlatives. Just like adjectives, possessive pronouns correspond with the noun they modify in gender, number and case. Except for the masculine nominative and accusative singular, their declension is identical to that of adjectives (moj, tvoj, na≈°, va≈°, svoj and ƒçij like svƒõ≈æi; jegov, jejin and jihny like dobry): Singular Plural m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. moj moje moja acc. mojego moj moju gen. mojego mojej dat. mojemu mojej ins. mojim mojeju loc. mojem mojej m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. moji moje acc. mojih gen. mojih dat. mojim ins. mojimi loc. mojih

The primary demonstrative pronoun is toj ‚Äûthis, that‚Äù, and it should be used whenever there is no need to distinguish explicitly between ‚Äûthis one over here‚Äù and ‚Äûthat one over there‚Äù. If we need to be more precise, the simplest solution is using tutoj for ‚Äûthis‚Äù and tamtoj for ‚Äûthat, yonder‚Äù. They are declined as follows: Singular Plural m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. toj to ta acc. togo toj tu gen. togo toj dat. tomu toj ins. tym toju loc. tom toj m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. ti te acc. tyh gen. tyh dat. tym ins. tymi loc. tyh

Less simple, but historically more accurate, is the following three-way distinction: sej (f. sa, n. se) for ‚Äûthis‚Äù, toj for ‚Äûthat‚Äù and onoj for ‚Äûyonder‚Äù. It should be remembered, however, that sej has practically vanished from most modern languages except for a few fossilized remnants. It may therefore not always be clear. Another demonstrative pronoun is ov, meaning the same thing as sej. However, its meaning is very different in the modern languages. Tutoj, tamtoj, ov and onoj are declined like toj. Instead of the plurals tyh, tym and tymi one might sometimes encounter tƒõh, tƒõm and tƒõmi.

The relative pronoun that is used most frequently is ktory. It is inflected like an ordinary adjective. Alternatively, South Slavic koj (inflected like moj) can be used as well. Their meanings are identical and they can be used interchangably. A third option is the more archaic i≈æe ‚Äì used in the nominative for all genders, both singular and plural; in other cases it is inflected like a form of the personal pronoun on/ona/ono with the suffix -≈æe: m.gen. sg. jego≈æe, m.dat. sg. jemu≈æe etc.

The interrogative pronouns are kto ‚Äûwho‚Äù and ƒçto (or ≈°to) ‚Äûwhat‚Äù. They are inflected as follows: who? what? nom. kto ƒçto acc. kogo gen. ƒçego dat. komu ƒçemu ins. kym ƒçim loc. kom ƒçem Interrogative determiners are koj (inflected like moj) ‚Äûwhich‚Äù (instead, ktory can be used as well), the possessive pronoun ƒçij ‚Äûwhose‚Äù (see above), and the adjective kaky ‚Äûwhat kind of‚Äù.

This is a large group of pronouns and determiners, most of which are derived regularly from the interrogative pronouns. There are several categories: Referring to all items (universal) (vs-): vsi or vsekto ‚Äûeveryone, everybody‚Äù, vse or vseƒçto ‚Äûeverything‚Äù; ves (f. vsa, n. vse ‚Äûwhole, entire; all‚Äù); cƒõly ‚Äûwhole, entire‚Äù; vsaky ‚Äûeach, every‚Äù; vsekaky ‚Äûeach kind of, all sorts of‚Äù; vseƒçij ‚Äûeverybody's‚Äù. Refering to no items (negative) (ni-): nikto ‚Äûno one, nobody‚Äù, niƒçto ‚Äûnothing‚Äù, nikoj, nijedin and nikaky ‚Äûnot a single, none‚Äù, niƒçij ‚Äûnobody's‚Äù. Referring a single unspecified item (nƒõ-): nƒõkto ‚Äûsomeone, somebody‚Äù, nƒõƒçto ‚Äûsomething‚Äù, nƒõkoj ‚Äûsome‚Äù, nƒõkaky ‚Äûsome kind of‚Äù, nƒõƒçij ‚Äûsomeone's, somebody's‚Äù. Referring to several unspecified items (ponƒõ‚Äì): ponƒõkoj ‚Äûsome, several‚Äù, ponƒõkaky ‚Äûseveral kinds of‚Äù. Referring to a large group of items: mnogy ‚Äûmuch, many, a lot of‚Äù. Referring to any member of a group (-koli, -nebud, libo-): ktokoli, libokto, kto-nebud ‚Äûanyone, anyone‚Äù, ƒçtokoli, liboƒçto, ƒçto-nebud ‚Äûanything‚Äù; kojkoli, libokoj, koj-nebud ‚Äûany‚Äù, kakykoli, libokaky, kaky-nebud ‚Äûany kind of‚Äù; ƒçijkoli, liboƒçij, ƒçij-nebud ‚Äûanyone's, anybody's‚Äù. To indicate indifference, the adverb bylo can be used: bylo kto ‚Äûno matter who, just anybody‚Äù, bylo ƒçto ‚Äûno matter what‚Äù, etc. Referring to another item of a group (in-): inokto ‚Äûsomeone else‚Äù, inoƒçto ‚Äûsomething else‚Äù, iny ‚Äûother‚Äù, inoƒçij ‚Äûsomeone else's‚Äù. Vsekto, nikto, nƒõƒçto, ƒçtokoli etc. are inflected like kto and ƒçto. Likewise, nikoj, nƒõƒçij etc. are inflected like koj and ƒçij (and thus like moj). Ves is inflected as follows: Singular Plural m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. ves vse vsa acc. vsego ves vsu gen. vsego vsej dat. vsemu vsej ins. vsim vseju loc. vsem vsej m. (animate) m. (inanimate) n. f. nom. vsi vse acc. vsih gen. vsih dat. vsim ins. vsimi loc. vsih

One of Zamenhof's best inventions was his table of correlatives, a group of interrelated pronouns, adjectives and adverbs. There words have been kept as regular as possible, but not at the expense of recognisability for speakers of Slavic languages. A few virtually impossible words have been left out, and a few other regular forms have been replaced by forms that are common in the natural languages. Irregular forms (i.e. not looking the way they should according to the table) are shown in italics. question k- here s- there t- yonder on- some nƒõk- several ponƒõk- any k-nebud, k-koli no nik- every vs- else in- which? koj sej, tutoj toj, tamtoj onoj nƒõkoj ponƒõkoj koj-nebud kojkoli nikoj, nijedin vsaky iny who? kto nƒõkto ‚Äî kto-nebud ktokoli nikto vsekto, vsi inokto what? ƒçto se to ono nƒõƒçto ponƒõƒçto ƒçto-nebud ƒçtokoli niƒçto vseƒçto, vse inoƒçto how much? koliko seliko toliko onoliko nƒõkoliko ‚Äî koliko-nebud kolikokoli ‚Äî whose? ƒçij ‚Äî nƒõƒçij ‚Äî ƒçij-nebud ƒçijkoli niƒçij vseƒçij inoƒçij what kind of? kaky saky taky onaky nƒõkaky ponƒõkaky kaky-nebud kakykoli nikaky vsaky inaky how? kako sako tako onako nƒõkako ponƒõkako kako-nebud kakokoli nikako vsako inako where? kde sde, tu tude, tam onde nƒõkde ponƒõkde kde-nebud kdekoli nikde vesde inde whereto? kamo samo tamo onamo nƒõkamo ‚Äî kamo-nebud kamokoli nikamo vsamo inamo when? kogda segda, sejƒças togda onogda nƒõkogda ponƒõkogda kogda-nebud kogdakoli nikogda vsegda inogda whither? kudy sudy tudy onudy nƒõkudy ‚Äî kudy-nebud kudykoli nikudy vsudy inudy whence? odkudy odsudy odtudy odonudy odnƒõkudy ‚Äî odkudy-nebud odkudykoli odnikudy odvsudy odinudy why (purpose)? ƒçemu ‚Äî tomu ‚Äî nƒõƒçemu ‚Äî ƒçemu-nebud ƒçemukoli niƒçemu ‚Äî ‚Äî why (reason)? zaƒçto ‚Äî zato ‚Äî zanƒõƒçto ‚Äî zaƒçto-nebud zaƒçtokoli zaniƒçto ‚Äî ‚Äî Notes In all cases when koj appears, ktory can be used interchangeably. In all cases when -gda appears, -gdy can be used interchangeably. Legal information This article has been republished with the permission of its original author, Jan van Steenbergen.

Word order is basically free, but the preferred (and stylistically most neutral) word order is subject ‚Äì verb ‚Äì object (SVO). It is not mandatory, but note that placing the object before the subject will not help in making clear the meaning. This is not the case of sentences where either a personal pronoun or the pronoun kto is either subject or object, because personal pronouns and kto have their own accusative forms, so the meaning is always clear. Modifiers usually precede the noun. This is not mandatory either, but it is the most neutral and the clearest way of building a sentence. There are two types of questions: Yes-no questions can be made in three different ways: either it differs from a normal declarative sentence only by intonation: Otec kupil knigu? ‚ÄûHas father bought a book?‚Äù or this sentence is preceded by the particle ƒçi: ƒåi otec kupil knigu? or it is marked by the question particle li placed right after the focus point of the question, usually the verb: Kupil li otec knigu? Other questions start with an interrogative pronoun or adverb, placed at the beginning of the sentence: Koju knigu kupil otec? ‚ÄûWhich book has father bought?‚Äù Kde otec kupil tu knigu? ‚ÄûWhere did father buy that book?‚Äù In this type of sentences, the meaning is usually made clear by the case that's been used: Koja ≈æena ljubi togo mu≈æa? ‚ÄûWhich woman loves that man?‚Äù (woman = subject, man = object) Koju ≈æenu ljubi toj mu≈æ? ‚ÄûWhich woman does that man love?‚Äù (man = subject, woman = object) If necessary, it is possible to use passive sentences that are always clear: Koja ≈æena jest ljubjena od togo mu≈æa? ‚ÄûWhich woman is loved by that man?‚Äù Final clauses are translated by means of ≈æe or da followed by the conditional: Turisti posƒõtet Niderlandiju, ≈æe by fotografovali tulipany. ‚ÄûTourists visit the Netherlands to take photos of the tulips.‚Äù Turisti posƒõtili Niderlandiju, ≈æe by fotografovali tulipany. ‚ÄûTourists visited the Netherlands to take photos of the tulips.‚Äù Ona prinosi jabloka, da by dƒõti byli zdrave. ‚ÄûShe brings apples so that the kids will be healthy.‚Äù Ona prinosila jabloka, da by dƒõti byli zdrave. ‚ÄûShe brought apples so that the kids would be healthy.‚Äù The passive voice can be used, but if so, it should be done with caution. A sentence like: Pica je dƒõlana or Pica je dƒõlajema ‚ÄûPizza is being made‚Äù is grammatically completely correct. Still, it can better be avoided, because a construction like that sounds clumsy to those Slavs who are not accustomed to using the verb ‚Äûto be‚Äù very often, especially in the present tense. Besides, while it is perfectly natural for part of the Slavic speakers, for others the past passive participle cannot be used for a present tense construction at all. Therefore, if the subject is known, it is better to utilise a normal active sentence. And if the subject isn't known, as in the case of our pizza, it is possible to use third person plural form without the subject: Dƒõlajut picu ‚ÄûThey make pizza, one makes pizza, pizza is being made‚Äù. Even more common is a reflexive construction: Pica dƒõlaje se, which literally means ‚ÄûPizza is making itself‚Äù and should be translated as ‚ÄûOne makes pizza, pizza is being made‚Äù.
