Simplified grammar, or Slovianto, is a highly simplified form of Interslavic that allows non-Slavic people to express themselves at a very basic level when visiting Slavic countries or maintaining contact with Slavs via the Internet. Grammar is limited to a bare minimum, and forms that are not strictly necessary are not used at all. Because it does not contain anything that cannot be found in the Slavic languages, the result wil not look or sound too awkward to Slavic speakers, but rather remind them of the kind of language used by small children. Slovianto can also be used as a first step in the process of learning the ‚Äûreal‚Äù Interslavic language. It has been constructed in such way that it can gradually be expanded with new bits and pieces that occur in more complex versions. Thus, we distinguish three different levels, each of them adding new elements that bring Slovianto closer to Interslavic: Level 1 ‚Äì the simplest level: no gender, no cases, only singular/plural, one verb ending per tense Level 2 ‚Äì introduction to gender, simple model for conjugating verbs (things that can be found in all Slavic languages) The working title Slovianto is a portmanteau word for ‚ÄûSlavic Esperanto‚Äù. This name, albeit somewhat tongue-in-cheek, refers to the simplicity of Slovianto: it has no gender, no cases, no aspect, little conjugation and no irregularity. Yet, that is where the similarity to Esperanto ends, because Slovianto's means of simplification are in fact far more similar to those used by Interlingua.
Explore the simplified grammar of Interslavic, or Slovianto, for a basic linguistic comparison.
Explore the more advanced grammar of Slovianto, a simplified form of Interslavic, for a basic linguistic comparison.

Slovianto can be written in the Latin alphabet and the Cyrillic alphabet, but we will concentrate on the Latin alphabet here: A ‚Äì as a in English father B ‚Äì as in English C ‚Äì as ts in English ‚Äûbits‚Äù ƒå ‚Äì as ch in English ‚Äûchurch‚Äù D ‚Äì as in English D≈Ω ‚Äì as j in English ‚ÄûJohn‚Äù E ‚Äì as e in English ‚Äûbest‚Äù ƒö ‚Äì as ye in English ‚Äûyet‚Äù F ‚Äì as in English G ‚Äì as g in English ‚Äûgood‚Äù H ‚Äì as ch in Scottish ‚Äûloch‚Äù I ‚Äì as ea in English ‚Äûbeat‚Äù J ‚Äì as y in English ‚Äûyard‚Äù K ‚Äì as in English, but without aspiration L ‚Äì as in English LJ ‚Äì as li in English ‚Äûmillion‚Äù M ‚Äì as in English N ‚Äì as in English NJ ‚Äì as ny in English ‚Äûcanyon‚Äù O ‚Äì as o in English ‚Äûor‚Äù P ‚Äì as in English, but without aspiration R ‚Äì rolled r RJ ‚Äì rolled r, followed by ye as in English ‚Äûyet‚Äù S ‚Äì as s in English ‚Äûspin‚Äù ≈† ‚Äì as sh in English ‚Äûshop‚Äù T ‚Äì as in English, but without aspiration U ‚Äì as oo in English ‚Äûbook‚Äù V ‚Äì as v in English ‚Äûavoid‚Äù Y ‚Äì as i in English ‚Äûbit‚Äù Z ‚Äì as in English ≈Ω ‚Äì as si in English ‚Äûvision‚Äù In the Interslavic dictionary you will find other characters as well, like √≤, ≈≥, √• or ≈•. You can simply ignore the diacritics and read them as o, u, a, t etc. That goes for ƒõ, too. The only characters that keep their diacritics in Latin orthography are ƒç, ≈° and ≈æ. If you find writing them inconvenient, you can always use cz, sz and zs (or cx, sx and zx) as an alternative. Accentuation is fairly free. What matters more is that you speak slowly and clearly. As a general guideline, it would deserve recommendation to put stress on the antepenultimate syllable.

Nouns can end in a consonant or -a, -o, -e. Slovianto does not have articles. Therefore, ≈æena can mean ‚Äûa woman‚Äù or ‚Äûthe woman‚Äù. The plural is formed by adding -i if the word ends in a consonant, or by replacing the final vowel by -i: mu≈æ ‚Äûman‚Äù ‚Üí mu≈æi ‚Äûmen‚Äù ≈æena ‚Äûwoman‚Äù ‚Üí ≈æeni ‚Äûwomen‚Äù slovo ‚Äûword‚Äù ‚Üí slovi ‚Äûwords‚Äù

Adjectives usually have the ending -y or -i. They are not inflected and should be placed before the noun. An adjective can be made into an adverb by substituting -y with the ending -o: dobry ‚Äûgood‚Äù ‚Üí dobro ‚Äûwell‚Äù Adjectives are compared by means of the words vy≈°e (‚Äûmore‚Äù), menje (‚Äûless‚Äù), naj- (‚Äûmost‚Äù) and najmenje (‚Äûleast‚Äù): dobry ‚Äûgood‚Äù vy≈°e dobry ‚Äûbetter‚Äù naj-dobry ‚Äûbest‚Äù menje dobry ‚Äûless good‚Äù najmenje dobry ‚Äûleast good‚Äù

Unlike nouns, personal pronouns in Slovianto distinguish between the nominative (the subject of the sentence, the agent) and the accusative (the object, patient). The subject forms are: ja ‚ÄûI‚Äù, ty ‚Äûyou (sg.), thou‚Äù, on ‚Äûhe‚Äù, ona ‚Äûshe‚Äù, my ‚Äûwe‚Äù, vy ‚Äûyou (pl.)‚Äù, oni ‚Äûthey‚Äù. The object forms are: mene ‚Äûme‚Äù, tebe ‚Äûyou (sg.), thee‚Äù, jego ‚Äûhim‚Äù, ju ‚Äûher‚Äù, nas ‚Äûus‚Äù, vas ‚Äûyou (pl.)‚Äù, jih ‚Äûthem‚Äù. Like most natural Slavic languages, Interslavic has T-V distinction, i.e. vy and vas are used not only for the second person plural, but also as a polite form in the singular. Ty/tebe are used to address friends, relatives and children. Slovianto also has a reflexive pronoun, se, meaning ‚Äûoneself, myself, yourself, ...‚Äù. It has no subject form, only an object form. This reflexive pronoun can also be used as a reciprocal pronoun. Oni myt se means: ‚Äûthey are washing themselves‚Äù, but can also mean: ‚Äûthey are washing each other‚Äù. A preposition is always followed by the accusative: s mene ‚Äûwith me‚Äù bez jego ‚Äûwithout him‚Äù za tebe ‚Äûbehind you‚Äù For the indirect object, the preposition k ‚Äûto, towards‚Äù can be added: Dajte k mene ... ‚ÄûGive me ...‚Äù

The possessive pronouns are: moj ‚Äûmy‚Äù, tvoj ‚Äûyour, thy‚Äù, jego ‚Äûhis, its‚Äù, jej ‚Äûher‚Äù, na≈° ‚Äûour‚Äù, va≈° ‚Äûyour (pl.)‚Äù, jih ‚Äûtheir‚Äù. Like adjectives, possessive pronouns are not inflected. If the possessor is also the subject of the sentence, the reflexive svoj ‚Äûone's own‚Äù is used for all persons. There are also interrogative and indefinite possessive pronouns, like ƒçij ‚Äûwhose‚Äù, niƒçij ‚Äûnobody's‚Äù, nƒõƒçij ‚Äûsomebody's‚Äù, ƒçij-koli ‚Äûanybody's‚Äù.

The demonstrative pronoun is toj ‚Äûthis, that, these, those‚Äù. Whenever it is necessary to make a distinction between here and there, we have it preceded by tu- ‚Äûhere‚Äù or tam- ‚Äûthere‚Äù: tutoj ‚Äûthis, these‚Äù, tamtoj ‚Äûthat, those‚Äù. When used independently, use to: ƒåto jest to? ‚ÄûWhat is this?‚Äù To jest kniga. ‚ÄûThis is a book.‚Äù
In a simplified language like Slovianto, it is better to avoid subordinate clauses. But if you need a relative pronoun anyway, use ktory ‚Äûwhich‚Äù.

There are two basic pronouns: kto ‚Äûwho‚Äù and ƒçto ‚Äûwhat‚Äù. Just like personal pronouns, kto has an accusative kogo for the direct object. Derived from these are also several indefinite pronouns, e.g. nƒõkto ‚Äûsomebody‚Äù, kto-koli ‚Äûanybody‚Äù, niƒçto ‚Äûnothing‚Äù, vseƒçto ‚Äûeverything‚Äù (see the following section).

Every language has a special category of interrelated pronouns, adverbs and adjectives, the so-called correlatives. In short, these are question words and the words that are used to give a general answer to these questions. In English, as well as many other languages, these words are related with each other in a fairly predictable way (for example: where/here/there/somewhere/anywhere/nowhere/everywhere, whence/hence/thence, etc.). This is the case in Slovianto, too. Question words usually start with a k-: kto ‚Äûwho‚Äù, kogda ‚Äûwhen‚Äù, kde ‚Äûwhere‚Äù, ktory ‚Äûwhich‚Äù, koliko ‚Äûhow many‚Äù If the answer is a specific thing, place etc., the word starts with t-: to ‚Äûthis, that‚Äù, togda ‚Äûthen‚Äù, toliko ‚Äûthis many‚Äù If the answer is something unknown or unspecified, the word starts with nƒõ- (followed by the question word): nƒõkto ‚Äûsomeone‚Äù, nƒõkogda ‚Äûsometime, one day‚Äù, nƒõkde ‚Äûsomewhere, someplace‚Äù If the answer is negative, the word begins with ni- (followed by the question word): nikto ‚Äûnobody‚Äù, nikogda ‚Äûnever‚Äù, nikde ‚Äûnowhere‚Äù If the answer is something unimportant, the word ends with -koli, added to the question word: kto-koli ‚Äûanyone‚Äù, kogda-koli ‚Äûanytime, whenever‚Äù, kde-koli ‚Äûanywhere, whereever‚Äù If the answer is all-encompassing, the word begins with vse- or ves-: vsegda ‚Äûalways‚Äù, vesde ‚Äûeverywhere‚Äù

The cardinal numbers from 1-10 are: 1 ‚Äì jedin, 2 ‚Äì dva, 3 ‚Äì tri, 4 ‚Äì ƒçetyri, 5 ‚Äì pet, 6 ‚Äì ≈°est, 7 ‚Äì sedm, 8 ‚Äì osm, 9 ‚Äì devet, 10 ‚Äì deset The ‚Äû-teens‚Äù (11-19) are formed by adding -nadset: 11 ‚Äì jedinnadset, 12 ‚Äì dvanadset, ... The ‚Äû-ties‚Äù (20, 30 ... 90) are formed by adding -deset: 20 ‚Äì dvadeset, 30 ‚Äì trideset, ... The ‚Äû-hundreds‚Äù (200, 300 ... 900) are formed by adding -sto: 200 ‚Äì dvasto, 300 ‚Äì tristo, ... Higher numbers: 1,000 ‚Äì tyseƒç, 1,000,000 ‚Äì milion, 1,000,000,000 ‚Äì miliard Combinations of these are always made from high to low: 5,678 ‚Äì pet-tyseƒç ≈°eststo sedmdeset osm Ordinal numbers are formed by adding -y to the corresponding cardinal number, except for the following: 1st ‚Äì prvy, 2nd ‚Äì drugy, 3rd ‚Äì tretji, 4th ‚Äì ƒçetvrty, 100th ‚Äì sotny or stoty, 1000th ‚Äì tyseƒçny

All verbs have the infinitive ending -ti: dƒõlati ‚Äûto do‚Äù prositi ‚Äûto ask‚Äù nesti ‚Äûto carry‚Äù The stem is obtained by removing the ending -ti from the infinitive: dƒõla- prosi- nes- At this early stage, one ending for the present tense will do. It is formed by adding -t to the stem. If the present tense stem ends in a consonant, -e- is inserted between the stem and the ending: ja dƒõla-t ‚ÄûI do‚Äù vy prosi-t ‚Äûyou ask‚Äù oni nes-et ‚Äûthey carry‚Äù And here's a bit of irregularity that happens so often in Slavic that you might as well learn it now: if the stem ends in k or g, these consonants become ƒç and ≈æ before the inserted e: pekti ‚Äûto bake‚Äù ‚Üí peƒçet mogti ‚Äûcan‚Äù ‚Üí mo≈æet For the past tense, add -l (singular) or -li (plural) to the stem: ja dƒõla-l ‚ÄûI did, I have done‚Äù on prosi-l ‚Äûhe asked‚Äù my nes-li ‚Äûwe carried‚Äù For the future tense, use bude with the infinitive: ja bude dƒõlati ‚ÄûI will do‚Äù my bude prositi ‚Äûwe will ask‚Äù oni bude nesti ‚Äûthey will carry‚Äù The conditional is formed by using the particle by with the past tense: ja by dƒõlal ‚ÄûI would do/I would have done‚Äù The imperative has the ending -jte after a vowel or -ite after a consonant: dƒõla-jte ‚Äûdo!‚Äù prosi-jte ‚Äûask!‚Äù nes-ite ‚Äûcarry!‚Äù The past passive participle is created by adding -ny to the stem. If the stem ends in a consonant, insert -e- between the stem and the ending. If the stem ends in -i-, then insert -e- and change resulting -ieny to -jeny: dƒõla-ny ‚Äûdone‚Äù nes-eny ‚Äûcarried‚Äù prosi-eny ‚Üí prosjeny ‚Äûasked‚Äù The verb byti ‚Äûto be‚Äù is irregular: present tense: jest past tense: byl, byli future tense: bude conditional: byl by, byli by imperative: budite The passive voice is created as in English, by combining a form of the verb byti ‚Äûto be‚Äù with the past passive participle: ja jest neseny ‚ÄûI am being carried‚Äù ja byl neseny ‚ÄûI was being carried, I have been carried‚Äù, etc.

The preferred word order is subject ‚Äì verb ‚Äì object, like in English. It isn't mandatory, but any other word order might easily make a sentence unclear or ambiguous. Adjectives, possessive pronouns and the like are preferably placed before the noun they modify: toj dobry kniga ‚Äûthis good book‚Äù Yes-no questions differ from normal indicative sentences only by intonation: Otec kupil kniga ‚ÄûFather has bought a book.‚Äù Otec kupil kniga? ‚ÄûHas father bought a book?‚Äù In other questions, the interrogative pronoun or adverb comes first: Kaky kniga kupil otec? ‚ÄûWhat kind of book has father bought?‚Äù Kde otec kupil toj kniga? ‚ÄûWhere did father buy that book?‚Äù The easiest way for expressing possession is simply placing the possessor before the possessed. When this is not clear enough, use the preposition od ‚Äûfrom, of‚Äù: moj otec kniga ‚Äûmy father's book‚Äù (lit. ‚Äûmy father book‚Äù) kniga od moj otec ‚Äûmy father's book‚Äù (lit. ‚Äûthe book of my father‚Äù) Likewise, you don't need to use any special accessories for the indirect object. Whenever this is not clear enough, use the preposition k ‚Äûto‚Äù: Dajte moj otec toj kniga. ‚ÄûGive that book to my father.‚Äù Dajte toj kniga k moj otec. ‚ÄûGive that book to my father.‚Äù To express the instrument used for something, use the preposition s ‚Äûwith‚Äù: Ja udaril svoj otec s toj kniga. ‚ÄûI hit my father with that book.‚Äù

In Level 1 you have learned a number of forms that can you can use to make yourself understandable to Slavs on a very basic level. This language, however, is very primitive, and doesn't do justice to the richness of the Slavic languages at all. So, if you are up to the challenge, here are some more tools that you can use to make Slovianto look and sound a lot more natural. Level 2 differs from Level 1 in two ways: You will learn about gender in Slavic and how to use it in Slovianto, You will learn how to conjugate verbs.

Most European languages have grammatical gender ‚Äì English is one of the very few exceptions. It is no more than logical that words denoting male persons are always masculine and words denoting female persons are always feminine. The idea of grammatical gender, however, is that every noun has a gender, even if there is no logical connection whatsoever between this gender and the meaning of the word. In French, for example, le vin ‚Äûthe wine‚Äù is masculine and la bi√®re ‚Äûthe beer‚Äù is feminine. In German, der Wein ‚Äûthe wine‚Äù is masculine as well, but das Bier ‚Äûthe beer‚Äù is neuter. The gender of a noun affects not only the article, but also adjectives, possessive pronouns and other words that modify this noun. French has un bon vin froid ‚Äûone good cold wine‚Äù, but une bonne bi√®re froide ‚Äûone good cold beer‚Äù. All Slavic languages have three genders: masculine, feminine and neuter. At the first level of Slovianto, gender does not play a role, because it is not essential for communication on the most basic level. Small children often make mistakes with gender, but can still be understood. Which does not change the fact that dobry ≈æena ‚Äûa good woman‚Äù sounds clumsy, because ≈æena is feminine and the ending -y is masculine. You can make your Slovianto look and sound a lot more natural if you also take into account gender. Establishing the gender of a noun is not difficult at all, because in almost all cases, looking at the word is enough to know its gender, which means that there is no need to learn the gender separately.

To find out whether a word is masculine, feminine or neuter, it is enough to look at the ending: Masculine words always end in a consonant: mu≈æ ‚Äûman‚Äù syn ‚Äûson‚Äù dom ‚Äûhouse‚Äù Words on -a are feminine: ≈æena ‚Äûwoman, wife‚Äù du≈°a ‚Äûsoul‚Äù voda ‚Äûwater‚Äù Words on -o and -e are neuter: slovo ‚Äûword‚Äù dƒõte ‚Äûchild‚Äù morje ‚Äûsea‚Äù There is also a group of feminine words ending in a consonant. As a rule of thumb, remember that most of these are words ending on -ost: kost ‚Äûbone‚Äù velikost ‚Äûgreatness‚Äù There are a few exceptions, but you don't need to worry about them at this point. At the first level, you have learned that the plural ending is -i. That works well for masculine and feminine nouns, however, in the case of neuter nouns it is better to use -a instead: slovo ‚Üí slova ‚Äûwords‚Äù dƒõte ‚Üí dƒõta ‚Äûchildren‚Äù morje ‚Üí morja ‚Äûseas‚Äù

Not only nouns have gender, the same goes for adjectives and similar modifiers, too. Just like in French and German, the Slavic languages have gender agreement. This means that when a masculine noun is accompanied by an adjective, this adjective takes the masculine form, a feminine noun takes the feminine form of the adjective, etc. Dobry ≈æena looks a bit childish and clumsy, because it combines a feminine noun with a masculine adjective. So remember the following things: The masculine ending is -y or -i. This is the form given in the dictionary: dobry mu≈æ ‚Äûa good man‚Äù The feminine ending is -a: dobra ≈æena ‚Äûa good woman‚Äù The neuter ending is -e: dobre dƒõte ‚Äûa good child‚Äù For all genders the plural ending is -e: dobre mu≈æi ‚Äûgood men‚Äù dobre ≈æeni ‚Äûgood woman‚Äù dobre dƒõta ‚Äûgood children‚Äù The same thing that goes for adjectives, goes also for possessive, demonstrative, relative, indefinite pronouns, as well as for numbers. The possessive pronouns moj ‚Äûmy‚Äù, tvoj ‚Äûyour, thy‚Äù, na≈° ‚Äûour‚Äù, va≈° ‚Äûyour (pl.)‚Äù, svoj ‚Äûone's own‚Äù and ƒçij ‚Äûwhose‚Äù receive the same endings as adjectives (except in the masculine): moj (m.), moja (f.), moje (n.), moje (pl.). The same goes for the interrogative pronoun koj ‚Äûwhich‚Äù: moj mu≈æ ‚Äûmy husband‚Äù tvoja ≈æena ‚Äûyour wife‚Äù na≈°e dƒõte ‚Äûour child‚Äù koje prijatelji ‚Äûwhich friends‚Äù Possessive pronouns of the third person (jego ‚Äûhis, its‚Äù, jej ‚Äûher‚Äù, jih ‚Äûtheir‚Äù) do not alter (this is because these words are not strictly possessive pronouns, but literally mean something like ‚Äûof him‚Äù, etc.): jego ≈æena ‚Äûhis wife‚Äù jih prijatelji ‚Äûtheir friends‚Äù The demonstrative pronoun toj has the forms ta (f.), to (n.) and te (pl.), instead of *toja, *toje... (the same goes, of course, for tutoj and tamtoj): toj mu≈æ ‚Äûthis man‚Äù ta ≈æena ‚Äûthat woman‚Äù to dƒõte ‚Äûthis child‚Äù te prijatelji ‚Äûthese friends‚Äù The relative pronoun ktory behaves like an adjective: ≈æena, ktora ƒçita ‚Äûa woman who reads‚Äù dƒõte, ktore ja vidƒõl ‚Äûthe child that I've seen‚Äù The number jedin ‚Äûone‚Äù has the forms jedna (f.) and jedno (n.): jedin mu≈æ ‚Äûone man‚Äù jedna ≈æena ‚Äûone woman‚Äù jedno dƒõte ‚Äûthis child‚Äù

infinitive dƒõla-ti prosi-ti nes-ti ja dƒõla-m prosi-m nes-e-m ty dƒõla-≈° prosi-≈° nes-e-≈° on/ona/ono dƒõla prosi nes-e my dƒõla-mo prosi-mo nes-e-mo vy dƒõla-te prosi-te nes-e-te oni dƒõla-j-ut prosi-j-ut nes-ut In Slovianto level 1 you have learned that the present tense is formed by adding the ending -(e)t to the stem: ja dƒõla-t "I do", vy prosi-t "you ask", oni nes-et "they carry". To the Slavic ear, however, this sounds unnatural, because all Slavic languages inflect their verbs for person and number. To make a better impression, there is a lot to be gained by learning some of these personal endings as well. So, time to forget the ending -t! Instead, remember the following endings: -m, -≈°, -√ò (no ending) in the first, second and third person singular, and -mo, -te, -ut in the first, second and third person plural. When the stem ends in a vowel, insert -j- before the ending -ut. When the stem ends in a consonant, insert -e- before the remaining endings. See the table to the right for some examples. The ending -≈° and the personal pronoun ty should be used only for family, friends, children etc. In other cases, address people in the second person plural (vy, -te).

infinitive dƒõla-ti prosi-ti nes-ti ja (m.), ty (m.), on dƒõla-l prosi-l nes-l ja (f.), ty (f.), ona dƒõla-la prosi-la nes-la ono, to dƒõla-lo prosi-lo nes-lo my, vy, oni dƒõla-li prosi-li nes-li In the past tense, verbs are not conjugated for person. However, they are conjugated for gender. This may seem odd, but the explanation is pretty simple: the form dƒõlal is actually a participle, meaning something like ‚Äûhaving done‚Äù, and that's why it agrees with the subject in gender and number, but not in person. The forms are those shown in the table to the right.

The future tense is formed by combining the future tense of the verb byti ‚Äûto be‚Äù with the infinitive. The forms are the same as if a verb *bud-ti were conjugated in the present tense: ja budem dƒõlati, ty bude≈° dƒõlati, on bude dƒõlati, etc.

The conditional is formed by adding the particle by to the past tense, and therefore subject to gender agreement: ja by dƒõlal ‚ÄûI (m.) would do/have done‚Äù, ty by dƒõlala ‚Äûyou (f.) would do/have done‚Äù, my by dƒõlali ‚Äûwe would do/have done‚Äù.

infinitive dƒõla-ti prosi-ti nes-ti 2nd sg. ("Do!") dƒõla-j prosi-j nes-i 2nd pl ("Do!") dƒõla-jte prosi-jte nes-ite 1st ("Let's do!") dƒõla-jmo prosi-jmo nes-imo Apart from the imperative form you have already learned (the 2nd person plural), there are also imperative forms for the 2nd person singular and the 1st person plural. The endings are -j (2 sg.), -jmo (1 pl.) and -jte (2 pl.) after a vowel, and -i (2 sg.), -imo (1 pl.) and -ite (2 pl.) after a consonant. Thus, dƒõlajte means ‚Äûdo!‚Äù and can be directed at more people at once, but also serve as a more polite singular form, while dƒõlaj should only be used for friends, family and children. Dƒõlajmo means: ‚ÄûLet's do‚Äù.

Interslavic English Na≈°e selo‚Äã Iz vse mo≈ælive mƒõsta, kde ≈æijut ljudi, ja naj-mnogo ljubim male selo, daleko od ≈°umny grad, s jego mala spoleƒçnost. Ono ne ima prƒõpolnjene bloki, jedino male drevenne domki. Jest to proste i malovatelne mƒõsto dlja ≈æitje, s ≈æiteli, ƒçije lica sut ravno znane kak cvƒõti v na≈° sad. To jest zatvorjeny svƒõt s nemnogo ljudi, blizko sjedinjene kak mravki v mravska kopa, pƒçeli v pƒçelnik, ovci v ovƒçarnija, mni≈°ki v konvent, ili morniki na korabja ‚Äì kde vsekto zna vsekogo i vsekto jest znany od vsekogo, kde vsekto interesova se v vsekogo i vsekto mo≈æe imati nadeja, ≈æe nekto interesova se v jego. Kak milo bylo by zanuriti se v to srdeƒçne ƒçutje od ljubjenje i neznane obiƒçaji, sobrati se i byti prijatelji s te vse jedinstvene ljudi okolo nas! Tako, ≈æe my budemo znati vse zakutki i povrati od tenke ulici i solneƒçne luki, ktore my prohodimo vsaki denj. Mala socialna grupa, ktora jest selska spoleƒçnost, jest to, za ƒçto poezija i proza blagodarijut naj-mnogo. Dolga, raztegnjena draga, ktora bludi se v mily, teply denj i prƒõhodi ƒçrƒõz velika, ≈°iroka draga, polna od avta i tiri. Vy hoƒçete putovati s mene, dragi ƒçitatelj? Put ne bude dolgy. My naƒçinamo na dolina konec i odtudy my budemo pohoditi v vrh. Our village‚Äã Of all the possible places where people live, the one I love most is a small village far from the noise of the city, with its small community. It does not have overcrowded flats, just small wooden cottages. It is a simple and picturesque place to live, with inhabitants whose faces are as familiar as the flowers in our garden. It is a secluded world with few people, closely united like ants in an ant-hill, or bees in a hive, or sheep in a fold, or nuns in a convent, or sailors on a ship ‚Äì where everyone knows everyone and everyone is known by everyone, where everyone is interested in everyone, and everyone may hope that others are interested in him. How pleasant it would be to immerse oneself into this warm-hearted feeling of love and unknown habits, to get together and be friends with all these unique people around us! Just like we will know all the corners and turns of the shady streets and sunny meadows that we pass every day. The small social group, which is rural society, is what poetry and prose owe most to. A long, stretched out street, windingon a nice, warm day, crossing a large, broad road, full of cars and trucks. Would you like to travel with me, dear reader? The journey will not be long. We begin at the end of the valley and from there we will proceed up the hill. Legal information This article has been republished with the permission of its original author, Jan van Steenbergen.

Words are based on the living Slavic languages, and when the latter are not in agreement with each other, we basically follow the majority by applying a voting system. To avoid inconsistencies, we have to make sure that words using the same root always use it in the same form. Because all Slavic languages derive their forms from Common Slavic in a fairly predictable way, we never borrow from them directly. Instead, we follow a model for simple derivation from Common Slavic. This makes the language both easier to recognise and easier to use for everybody. Just by reading a few texts, a person will automatically learn quickly how a given sound in his own language is represented in Interslavic. Please note that in some cases it is possible to distinguish between a North and a South Slavic version (see flavourisation). The Slavs do not live on an island, and over the centuries their languages have borrowed many non-Slavic words as well. Part of those words were taken from their direct neighbours (German, Romance, Turkish). Vocabulary of this type has rarely found its way to the entire language family. For example, German loans are much more frequent in West Slavic than in Russian or Bulgarian, while words of Turkish descent can be found in South Slavic more abundantly than in the other Slavic languages. As a result, most of this vocabulary is not commonly understood and therefore not used in Interslavic. Another category is international vocabulary, mostly from Latin and Greek, but later also from French and more recently English. Words of this type tend to be similar throughout Europe and other parts of the world. They constitute an integral part of every Slavic language and can be of great help in achieving mutual intelligibility, especially among the more educated. International words are practically identical in every language, and there are hardly any variations in meaning. When we borrow international vocabulary, we stay as close as possible to spelling of the original word, adapting it only as far as orthography requires. However, especially for Graeco-Latin vocabulary goes the following: Geminated consonants are avoided: gramofon, grupa. The Greek consonants th (Œ∏) and ph (œÜ) are simplified to t and f: teatr, fenomen Greek y (œÖ) is written i, which is closer to both spelling and pronunciation in most Slavic languages: sistem, fizika The k sound is always written k and never c: kontakt The x sound (often represented by ch) is written h: psiholog. The y sound (in German written √º, in French u) becomes ju: bjuro. Between vowels, the z sound (written -s-) becomes z: baza. Between vowels, the s sound (written -ss-) becomes s: masa. Besides, endings are adapted in a predictable way to what is most common in the Slavic languages: Verbs of Latin descent (often -ate, -fy, -ise/-ize in English, -ieren in German) have -ovati: organizovati, komunikovati. Latin -ia (rendered in English as -ia or -y) becomes -ija: ekonomija. English -sis (from Greek) becomes -za: kriza. Names of chemical elements etc. on -ium become -ij: helij, kriterij. Words on -um and -us generally keep these endings: forum, korpus. English -ty (Latin -tas, -tatis) becomes -tet: universitet. English -ics becomes -ika: ekonomika. English -ism becomes -izm: komunizm. English -ist becomes -ist: komunist. English -ssion becomes -sija: diskusija. English -nsion, -rsion etc. become -nsija, -rsija etc.: pensija, versija. English -sion becomes -zija: televizija. English -tion becomes -cija: akcija. Adjectives derived from these nouns have the ending -ijny: televizijny, tradicijny. English adjectives in -al (Latin -alis) end in -alny: neutralny. English adjectives in -ic, -ical (Latin -icus) have the ending -iƒçny: specifiƒçny, komiƒçny. English adjectives in -ive (Latin -ivus) have the ending -ivny: pozitivny. English adjectives in -ous (Latin -osus) have the ending -ozny: seriozny. More problematic are words borrowed from English. When writing in the Latin alphabet, we can keep the original spelling (‚Äûbypass‚Äù, ‚Äûknockout‚Äù, ‚Äûjazz‚Äù, ‚Äûteenager‚Äù). However, many texts in Interslavic are written in Cyrillic or in both orthographies parallelly, often with the help of a transliteration program, and one should of course avoid writing –±—ã–ø–∞—Å—Å or –∫–Ω–æ—Ü–∫–æ—É—Ç in Cyrillic! In most cases, we would therefore rather apply a more phonetical approach: bajpas, nokaut, d≈æaz, tinejd≈æer, bud≈æet, biznes, mjuzikl, futbol, koktejl, etc. Legal information This article has been republished with the permission of its original author, Jan van Steenbergen.

Interslavic is meant to be as much at the centre of the Slavic languages as possible, and we do our best to offer solutions that are best for all Slavs together, avoiding characteristics of particular subgroups from predominating. These solutions, however, are not always ideal for communication between a subset of the Slavic speakers: what is best in Bulgaria or Croatia is not necessarily best in Poland or Russia. Interslavic should be flexible enough to offer solutions for all these different types of communication. This can be realised on four different levels: On a lexical level. Interslavic words have been selected for maximum intelligibility among the highest possible number of Slavs, but it is not always possible to find a word that is intelligible to all. Obviously, a word that is commonly understood by West and East Slavs but unknown to South Slavs will not be very helpful in the communication with Serbs or Bulgarians. For that reason, the dictionary sometimes offers synonyms, with one word covering one part of Slavic territory and a second word the other, enabling users to choose words that are intelligible to one subgroup in particular. On a phonological level. Even if a word occurs in all Slavic languages, it does not necessarily sound the same everywhere. For example, Russians and Ukrainians use korova for a cow, Poles and Sorbs krowa, Czechs, Slovaks and South Slavs krava. For a Russian, krova is easier to understand than krava, but there is no reason why Czechs and/or Slovaks should use it in communication with South Slavs, for instance. On an orthographical level. Written Interslavic can be made more familiar to speakers of particular languages by using an orthography similar to their own. For example, to accommodate Russian speakers, one might use —è, —é and –π instead of the forms with Cyrillic —ò. On a grammatical level. For example, by avoiding the use of infinitives and noun cases when addressing Bulgarians. The process of adding local colour to make Interslavic look and sound more familiar to speakers of particular languages is called ‚Äûflavourisation‚Äù. The possibilities are sheer endless: for every Slavic language or dialect, it is possible to create a ‚Äûnational‚Äù or ‚Äûregional‚Äù version, which in all likeliness will give a native speaker the impression of a funny yet perfectly understandable variation of his own language. In addition, flavourisation is achieved not only by adapting Interslavic to listener/reader, it is almost inevitably determined by the language of the speaker/writer, too. If you compare Interslavic written by a Pole and Interslavic written by a Serb, differences can easily be recognised. It would go way too far to describe every possible flavourised form of Interslavic. Let us therefore focus on forms intended for larger groups only, which can be realised by attributing more weight to understandability by some Slavs than by others. Because Interslavic uses a voting system as a tool for compilating words, grammatical endings and sounds, the outcome of a vote can change when certain languages are given less weight or eliminated altogether. Thus, instead of using the solutions that work best for all Slavs as a whole, we use characteristics that are typical for a subset of the Slavic languages only. The result can be described as ‚Äûdialects‚Äù, some more influenced by East Slavic, some more influenced by South Slavic, etc.

Flavorizacija v izgovoru The base for manipulating Interslavic is the etymological alphabet, a set of optional letters that do not really have a pronunciation of their own, but represent phonemes whose pronunciation varies from one language to another instead. In Interslavic, they can be used to convey additional etymological information, but they can also be used for a different purpose: by writing and/or pronouncing them in a different (non-standard) way, a text can be adapted to be better understood by speakers of a particular group of languages. The pronunciation of y differs from i only in Russian, Belarussian, Polish and Sorbian; in the South Slavic languages, in Ukrainian and in spoken Czech and Slovak, it merged with i. Thus, if you address an audience of South Slavs only, it is absolutely recommendable to replace all y with i. The vowel ƒõ merged with e into je (in Russian and Polish) or e (in Slovene, Serbian and Macedonian), but in the remaining languages it has variously developed into i, ije, je, ja or a (whereas e always remains hard e). As a result, the character ƒõ has excellent compromise qualities: a Serb can read rƒõƒç as his own reƒç, a Croat as his own rijeƒç, a Ukrainian as his own riƒç. For Russian and Poles, the distinction is irrelevant. Normally, the (historically nasal) vowel ƒô is written and pronounced like e, but this is a feature typical for South Slavic. A more North Slavic flavour can be achieved by substituting it with ja (after a soft consonant a). The vowel ≈≥ matches u in most Slavic languages, except Polish (ƒÖ/ƒô), Slovene (o), Macedonian (a) and Bulgarian (—ä). The letter √• does not exist in any Slavic language as a separate phoneme. Interslavic uses a in this position, as do Old Church Slavonic, South Slavic, Czech, Slovak and many words in Russian. To give the text a more North Slavic flavour, o can be used instead. The letter »Ø represents a strong hard jer (—ä). East Slavic, Slovak, Upper Sorbian and Macedonian have o here, Slovene and the remaining West Slavic languages e, Serbo-Croatian a and Bulgarian —ä (ƒÉ). Interslavic has o in this position, but for a more West Slavic flavour you can use e. The letter ƒó represents a strong soft jer (—å). In all Slavic languages, it has developed into e, except Serbo-Croatian, which has a. When r or ≈ï are preceded by a consonant and not followed by a vowel, they constitute a separate syllable, pronounced more less like «ùr and  ≤«ùr. In Czech, Slovak, Slovene, Serbo-Croatian and Macedonian, they merged into syllabic r. For a more North/East Slavic flavour, you can write or for syllabic r and er for syllabic ≈ï. The consonant g is pronounced more like an aspirated h in Ukrainian, Belarussian, Czech, Slovak and Upper Sorbian. Whereas Standard Interslavic has two softened consonants (lj and nj), the etymological alphabet has seven: ƒ∫ ≈Ñ ≈ï tÃÅ dÃÅ ≈õ ≈∫ (note that lj and nj are identical to ƒ∫ and ≈Ñ). The remaining five are largely absent in South Slavic, ≈õ ≈∫ also in Czech and Slovak and ≈ï in Slovak and Belarussian. If you want to give a text a more North-Slavic look-and-feel, it deserves recommendation to include them all. In that case it would of course be logical if all softened consonants were marked the same way: with the soft sign —å in Cyrillic, with an acute or a caron (h√°ƒçek) in Latin orthography. Instead of using ƒæ or ƒ∫ (both encountered in Slovak only), it is also possible to use l for the soft  é and ≈Ç for the hard l. This method is used in Polish, Sorbian and some forms of Belarusian ≈Åacinka and Ukrainian Latynka. The letters ƒá and ƒë are usually rendered as ƒç and d≈æ, but in a more South Slavic flavourisation they can be kept (written —õ and —í in Cyrillic). Never use —õ and —í for —Ç—å and –¥—å though, as these are separate etymological entities! At last, the sequence ≈°ƒç (Cyrillic: —à—á) can be flavourised ≈°t in a South Slavic. In Cyrillic, it can also be written —â. North and South‚Äã Again, the number of possible combinations between languages is almost endless, and it would go way too far to describe every possible flavourised form of Interslavic. The most obvious differences between the Slavic languages can be covered with two different flavourisation models (in addition to ‚Äûstandard‚Äù Interslavic): a more Northern-oriented one (focusing on Russian, Belarusian, Polish and Sorbian, with secondary focus on Czech, Slovak and Ukrainian), and a more Southern-oriented one (centered around South Slavic, also with secondary focus on Czech, Slovak and Ukrainian). Based on the previous paragraph, they could look as follows (the yellow fields are those where the flavourised form differs from the standard form): y ƒõ ƒô ≈≥ √• ƒó »Ø syll. r ≈ï lj/ƒ∫ nj/≈Ñ ≈ï tÃÅ dÃÅ ≈õ ≈∫ ƒá ƒë ≈°ƒç Northern y e ja u o e o or er ƒæ ≈Ñ/≈à ≈ï/≈ô ≈• ƒè ≈õ ≈∫ ƒç d≈æ ≈°ƒç Southern i ƒõ e u a e ƒÉ r lj nj r t d s z ƒá ƒë ≈°t In addition, in the Northern flavourisation infinitives end in -≈• instead of -ti, the nominative/accusative singular of adjectives should be -e instead of -o (dobre detja instead of Southern dobro dƒõte). The Northern flavourisation favours the relative pronoun ktory whereas the Southern flavourisation favours koj. Likewise, in the case of the prefix vy-/iz-, the former is North-oriented, the latter South-oriented. In the Southern flavourisation the preposition dlja ‚Äûfor‚Äù should be substituted with za.

Flavorizacija v pravopisanju Interslavic can be also made more accessible to certain groups by manipulating the way it is written. The standard Latin alphabet is mostly based on the Slovene alphabet, with the addition of y (from West Slavic) and ƒõ (from Czech and Sorbian). This alphabet, however, differs substantially from the Polish alphabet, and Polish speakers may not immediately understand letters like ƒõ or ≈°. To make it easier for them, one can for example replace v, ƒç, ≈°, ≈æ and ƒõ with w, cz, sz, ≈º and ie. Poles would also be helped by adopting ƒô and ≈≥ from the etymological alphabet, represented as iƒô and ƒÖ respectively. Below follows a list of suffixes. Please note that if the stem ends in a particular consonant, it is changed before the suffixes -ji, -ka, -ko, -nik, -ny, -ok, -sky and -stvo, as follows: k/c > ƒç (e.g. ruka > ruƒçny) g > ≈æ (e.g. kniga > kni≈æka) h > ≈° (e.g. muha > mu≈°ji) On the other hand, the soft consonant nj hardens before -nik and -ny. Suffixes starting with -o- change to -e- when following a soft consonant: byk + -ok > byƒçek konec + -ovy > koncevy noƒç + -ovati > noƒçevati Noun to noun‚Äã Diminutives are formed as follows: masculine words on a hard consonant have the suffix -ok: pes ‚Äûdog‚Äù > pesok (gen. peska) ‚Äûdoggy‚Äù masculine words on a soft consonant have the suffix -ik or -ek: mu≈æ ‚Äûman‚Äù > mu≈æik ‚Äûlittle man‚Äù feminine words add the suffix -ka to the word stem: kniga ‚Äûbook‚Äù > kni≈æka ‚Äûbooklet‚Äù neuter words add the suffix -ko to the word stem: polje ‚Äûfield‚Äù > poljko ‚Äûsmall field‚Äù To derive abstract qualities from names of persons, the suffix -stvo is used: prijatelj ‚Äûfriend‚Äù > prijateljstvo ‚Äûfriendship‚Äù, mu≈æ ‚Äûman‚Äù > mu≈æstvo ‚Äûmanhood‚Äù A place described as a preposition in combination with the name of another place usually has the ending -je: morje ‚Äûsea‚Äù > primorje ‚Äûland by the sea‚Äù, brjuh ‚Äûbelly‚Äù > podbrju≈°je ‚Äûunderbelly‚Äù A more general place indicator is the ending -i≈°ƒçe: voz ‚Äûwagon, car‚Äù > vozi≈°ƒçe ‚Äûparking lot‚Äù, ogonj ‚Äûfire‚Äù > ogni≈°ƒçe ‚Äûfireplace, hearth‚Äù To derive the person who is in charge of something or who is handling something, or the object that contains something, the suffix -nik is used: glava ‚Äûhead‚Äù > glavnik ‚Äûboss, chief‚Äù, kabel ‚Äûcable‚Äù > kabelnik ‚Äûcable guy‚Äù, The inhabitant of a country, region or city has the ending -ec (sometimes -an(in)): Albanija > Albanec ‚ÄûAlbanian‚Äù The female equivalent of the endings -nik and -ec is -nica and -ica respectively: rada ‚Äûcouncil‚Äù > radnik ‚Äûcounsellor‚Äù > radnica ‚Äûfemale counsellor‚Äù; Albanec ‚ÄûAlbanian‚Äù > Albanica ‚ÄûAlbanian woman‚Äù In other cases, we rather use the ending -ka for female equivalents of male persons: prijatelj ‚Äûfriend‚Äù > prijateljka ‚Äûgirl friend‚Äù, grad≈æanin ‚Äûcitizen‚Äù, grad≈æanka ‚Äûfemale citizen‚Äù A baby animal is usually derived by adding -e to the name of the animal, resulting in a neuter noun of the -et- class: kot ‚Äûcat‚Äù > kote ‚Äûkitten‚Äù, jelenj ‚Äûdeer‚Äù > jelene ‚Äûfawn‚Äù Adjective to noun‚Äã To derive an abstract quality from an Two roots can be freely compounded to create a new idea. Usually, this is done by means of a connecting -o- (-e- after a soft consonant): voda ‚Äûwater‚Äù + padati ‚Äûto fall‚Äù > vodopad ‚Äûwaterfall‚Äù sam ‚Äûself‚Äù + kritika ‚Äûcriticism‚Äù > samokritika ‚Äûself-criticism‚Äù my≈° ‚Äûmouse‚Äù + loviti ‚Äûcatch, hunt‚Äù > my≈°elovka ‚Äûmousetrap‚Äù zemja ‚Äûland, earth‚Äù + tresenje ‚Äûtrembling‚Äù > zemjetresenje ‚Äûearthquake‚Äù When the first member is a borrowing from English, they may be divided by a hyphen (defis): rok-muzika ‚Äûrock music‚Äù veb-stranica ‚Äûweb page‚Äù Legal information This article has been republished with the permission of its original author, Jan van Steenbergen.

Welcome to our carefully curated guide, dedicated to the world of the Interslavic language. We have an array of resources to facilitate your learning journey, from online communities and educational content to software tools and literature. Let's embark on this captivating linguistic adventure together.
Interact with fellow language enthusiasts and get involved in stimulating discussions in our vibrant social network communities.

Our Facebook community consists of over 18,000 members who share a passion for the Interslavic language. The guiding principle here is simple: We write either about Interslavic in any language or about anything in Interslavic language.
If you're in search of real-time interactions, join our Discord server with approximately 6,000 other members.
Join us on Reddit, another great platform for sharing knowledge and engaging in discussions about the Interslavic language.
Check out the Interslavic official channel and our comprehensive playlist of all Interslavic videos for insightful content: Interslavic Official Channel Interslavic Video Playlist
Our Interslavic Wiki is a rich knowledge repository where you can dive deep into the intricacies of the language.
Pub "Med≈æuslovjanska Kapibara" ‚Äì regularly updated with amusing content. Zapisky srƒõdnoevropskogo med≈æuslovjanina ‚Äì Roberto Lombino's microblog.
Listen to our recommended podcasts for a unique auditory learning experience: Interslavic News Med≈æuslovjansky Slovotok Radio Dupa FM
Sing along with the translations of your favorite songs in Interslavic on LyricsTranslate.

For reading practice, we recommend the following books: The Little Prince (Latin script): http://steen.free.fr/interslavic/maly_princ_lat.pdf The Little Prince (Cyrillic script): http://steen.free.fr/interslavic/maly_princ_kir.pdf Med≈æuslovjansky ƒåitateljnik: https://www.ceeol.com/search/chapter-detail?id=791191 "Slovjani" Magazine: https://slovjani.info - it has some articles in Interslavic, but it's not a language magazine.
You can find a handbook by Vojtech Merunka here and here.
Various software tools to assist in your learning process:
See the Keyboards page for more information.
Our online Interslavic dictionary is a comprehensive tool.
